1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nd2 (3. Nf3 $2 Nxe4 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. O-O g6 6. c4 Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O $17) (3. Bc4 Nxe4 ({the most principled reply;} 3... c6 {is also good enough}) 4. Bxf7+ Kxf7 5. Qh5+ Kg8 (5... g6 {may well be Black's most precise reaction -} 6. Qd5+ Ke8 7. Qxe4 {with the justification} Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7f5,Gd7g4] , aiming at exchanging the queens, after which the bishops' pair will play a significant role}) 6. Qd5+ e6 7. Qxe4 Nc6 8. Nf3 Qf6 $132 {[%cal Gc8d7]}) (3. Qd3 {is artificial -} e5 ({or} 3... Nbd7 4. c4 $140 e5) 4. Nf3 (4. dxe5 $6 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {has just dropped a tempo}) 4... Nbd7 5. Nc3 Be7 $11 {[%csl Rd3]}) (3. Qe2 {looks bizarre, White is keeping the option for c2-c4, but it is likely he will have to improve his queen pretty soon.} e5 (3... g6 $5) 4. Nf3 c6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd8a5]} (4... Nbd7 $144) 5. g3 (5. Nc3 Nbd7) (5. c4 Be7 6. Nc3 O-O $11 {[%csl Re2]}) ({almost symmetrical is} 5. c3 Qc7 6. Qc2 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Bg4 $1 9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. h3 Bh5 $11) 5... Be7 ({worth of serious attention is} 5... Bg4 6. dxe5 $140 dxe5 7. h3 Be6 8. Bg2 h6 9. O-O Qc7 10. Nbd2 Nbd7) 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O exd4 $5 (7... Qc7 {is quite decent, but Black is trying to use the drawback of Qe2 by opening the central file for his rook}) 8. Nxd4 Re8 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gd6d5]} 9. c4 (9. Nc3 Bf8 {[%cal Gb8a6,Gb7b5]}) 9... Qb6 $1 {is more ambitious, as Black is unambiguously fighting for the initiative:} (9... d5 $5 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. exd5 (11. e5 $6 Bd6 12. Bf4 Nc6 $15) 11... Nxd5 {must be approximately equal, though, in the view of the long-ranged Bg2, a precision is still required from Black, e.g.} 12. Nb5 (12. Nc3 Bf6) 12... Bf8) 10. Nb3 (10. Nf3 Nbd7 11. Be3 Qa6 12. Nd4 Ne5 13. b3 Nfg4 $1 14. Nc3 (14. Bd2 d5 $1 15. cxd5 Qxe2 16. Nxe2 cxd5 17. h3 (17. exd5 Bc5 18. Nbc3 Nd3 $44) 17... Nxf2 18. Rxf2 Bc5 19. Bc3 Bxf2+ 20. Kxf2 dxe4 $132) 14... Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Ng4 16. Qd2 Bd7 17. h3 Nf6 18. a4 Qa5 $11) ({in case of} 10. Rd1 {the break} d5 $1 {is much more to the point -} 11. cxd5 Bc5 $1 {(a key intermezzo)} 12. Be3 Bg4 13. f3 Rxe4 $132 14. fxg4 $140 Rxd4 15. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 16. Kh1 Bxb2 17. g5 Bxa1 18. gxf6 Na6 {(the only, but sufficient)} 19. fxg7 cxd5 $11) 10... Be6 $5 11. Be3 Qa6 {is pointing at the vulnerability of the c4-pawn again:} 12. Na3 ({White's knights are awkwardly placed after} 12. N1d2 {, they can be further restricted by} c5 $1 13. h3 Nc6 14. f4 Rad8 15. g4 h6 $1 $132) (12. Rc1 d5 13. Nd4 Bg4 14. f3 Bc8 15. cxd5 ({it is important that} 15. e5 {can be effectively countered with} dxc4 $132 {, when White is well-advised not to be greedy and take risks with} 16. exf6 $2 Bxf6) 15... Qxe2 16. Nxe2 cxd5 17. e5 Nc6 18. f4 (18. exf6 $2 Bxf6 $17 {[%cal Ge8e2]}) 18... Ng4 19. Bc5 Bxc5+ 20. Rxc5 Ne3 21. Bf3 f6 22. Nbc3 (22. exf6 Bg4 $1 $132) 22... Bg4 $1 23. Bxg4 Nxg4 24. Nxd5 Rad8 25. h3 Nh6 26. g4 fxe5 27. f5 Rd7 $11) 12... d5 $1 $132 13. exd5 ({Black is doing fine in the entertaining line} 13. e5 Ng4 14. Bf4 dxc4 15. Nd4 c3 $1 16. Rae1 $1 Qxe2 17. Rxe2 Bxa3 18. Nxe6 Rxe6 19. bxa3 Nd7 20. Bh3 h5 21. f3 g5 $1 22. fxg4 gxf4 23. gxf4 hxg4 24. Bxg4 Rg6 25. Rg2 Nc5 $132) 13... Bxd5 14. Bxd5 Nxd5 15. Nb5 $1 (15. Bd4 Nd7 $11) 15... cxb5 16. cxd5 {A clever tactics has helped White to create a passed pawn, but} Nd7 {blockades it steadily in advance.} 17. Nd4 Bg5 18. Ne6 $5 ({little is promised by} 18. Rad1 Bxe3 19. fxe3 Rad8 20. Nf5 Ne5 $11) ({or} 18. Qxb5 Qxb5 19. Nxb5 Bxe3 20. fxe3 Rxe3 $11) 18... fxe6 19. Bxg5 h6 20. Be3 exd5 21. Qd3 {and here Black's most active and based on the vulnerable light squares continuation is} Ne5 22. Qxd5+ Kh8 $11) 3... e5 ({Regarding the location of Nd2, it makes sense for Black to switch to the Pirc with} 3... g6) 4. c3 (4. Ngf3 exd4 $1 5. Nxd4 g6 {[%csl Rd2] is also aiming at taking advantage of the absence of the knight from its usual c3-square, e.g.} 6. Bd3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O $132 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gb8d7]}) (4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Ngf3 {is too modest -} Bc5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc4 Qe7 9. c3 a5 $11) (4. d5 c6 $5 (4... Be7 $11) 5. c4 b5 $132 {is worth comparing to the main line in Chapter 3.}) 4... exd4 $5 (4... Be7 {is arguably the best location for this bishop -} 5. Bd3 O-O 6. Ngf3 Nbd7 7. O-O $14) (4... Nc6 5. Ngf3 {is transposing to a rare line in the Ponziani}) ({As before,} 4... g6 {is quite playable -} 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Ngf3 Qe7 7. Bc4 Bh6 $5 8. O-O O-O) 5. cxd4 Qe7 $1 {The most concrete approach.} ({By the textmove Black is committing himself to a fianchetto, he can opt for it immediately -} 5... g6 6. Bd3 Bg7 7. Ne2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. h3 c5 10. d5 b6 11. Nc3 Ba6 $13) 6. Bd3 {The most natural reply.} (6. f3 g6 $132 {[%cal Gf8g7]}) (6. Ngf3 Nxe4 7. Bb5+ (7. Nxe4 Qxe4+ 8. Be2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Bf6 $132) 7... Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Nxd7 9. O-O d5 10. Re1 (10. Qb3 O-O-O) 10... O-O-O 11. Qb3 Ndf6 12. Ne5 Rg8 $132) (6. Qc2 Bf5 $1 {is initating a big skirmish in the center -} 7. f3 d5 $1 8. Bb5+ c6 9. Bd3 c5 $132 10. Ne2 Bg6 11. O-O (11. e5 Nfd7 12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. Qb3 Nb6 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 14. f4 Nc6 15. Nf3 cxd4 16. Nexd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Qb4+ 18. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 19. Bd2 Bxd2+ 20. Kxd2 g5 $11 {[%cal Gb6c4,Gh8h4]}) 11... Nc6 (11... c4 12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. Nxc4 $44 {[%cal Gc1f4]} {Black can also rely on} b5 ({Black can sensibly bet on development by means of} 13... Nbd7 14. Bf4 Qe6 15. Qb3 Be7 16. Qxb7 O-O 17. Rac1 Rfe8 18. d5 Bxe4 (18... Bc5+ $144 19. Kh1 Bxe4 20. dxe6) 19. dxe6 Bc5+ 20. Kh1 Bxb7 21. exd7 Rxe2 22. Na5 Nxd7 (22... Ba6 23. Rxc5 Nxd7 {may well be Black's easiest way to proceed -} 24. Rc7 Rxb2 25. Rfc1 Rxa2 ({or} 25... Nb6 26. Nc6 Nd5 27. Ne7+ Nxe7 28. Rxe7 Rxa2 29. Be3 Ra4 {with a sudden transposition}) 26. Rxd7 Rxa5 27. Be3 Ra4 28. Rcc7 Bc4 29. Rxa7 Ra1+ 30. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 31. Bg1 h6 {and it is time to sign a draw agreement}) 23. Nxb7 Bf8 $44 24. Rfd1 $140 Nf6 25. Rd2 Rxd2 26. Bxd2 Rb8 27. Rc7 Nd5 28. Rd7 Nf6 29. Rc7 Nd5 $11) 14. Ne5 Qb7 {, which looks solid enough, even though Bg6 is cut off and White is therefore not risking much, for example} 15. Bf4 Nbd7 16. Qc6 Qxc6 17. Nxc6 Nh5 18. Be3 f5 19. Nc3 fxe4 20. Nxb5 {with a probable repetition after} Rc8 21. Nbxa7 Ra8 22. Nb5 Rc8 $11) 12. Bb5 (12. Qa4 c4 13. exd5 {leads to a draw by force -} cxd3 14. dxc6 b5 15. Qxb5 dxe2 16. c7+ Qd7 17. Qb8+ Qc8 18. Qb5+ Qd7 $11) 12... Qc7 13. Qa4 (13. dxc5 Be7 $132) 13... dxe4 ({simpler is} 13... cxd4 14. Nxd4 Bc5 15. N2b3 Bb6 16. exd5 Nxd5 17. Re1+ Kf8 18. Kh1 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 h6 $11 {[%cal Gf8g8,Gg8h7]}) 14. Nxe4 (14. Nc4 {[%cal Gc1f4]} a6 15. Bf4 Qc8 16. Bxc6+ Qxc6 17. Qxc6+ bxc6 $132) 14... Nxe4 15. fxe4 cxd4 16. Bf4 Bd6 17. e5 Be7 18. Nxd4 O-O 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Bxc6 Qb6+ 21. Kh1 Rad8 22. b3 Rd4 23. Qb5 Qd8 $44 {[%cal Gg6d3]}) 6... Nxe4 $1 7. Nxe4 {Of course, Bd3 must be preserved.} ({White will be simply a pawn down after} 7. Ne2 $6 Nf6 8. O-O Qd8 $15 {[%cal Gf8e7]}) 7... d5 8. Bg5 (8. Nf3 dxe4 9. O-O exd3 {is fully playable -} 10. Re1 Be6 11. d5 Na6 $1 12. Bg5 Qd6 13. Re3 (13. dxe6 f6 {0-0-0}) 13... Nc5 (13... d2 $5 14. Re2 Be7 15. dxe6 O-O-O 16. exf7 Bxg5 17. Nxg5 Nc5 18. Nf3 Qg6 19. Rxd2 Qxf7 $11) 14. dxe6 Nxe6 15. Rc1 (15. Qb3 Qb6 {may result in a repetition after} 16. Qc3 Qc5 17. Qb3) 15... h6 16. Bh4 d2 17. Rc2 Qb4 $13) 8... Qe6 9. f3 {Securing the f2-square for the king in reply to a bishop check, which seems to work fine for Black after the rest continuations:} (9. Nh3 Bb4+ $1 ({gaining a precious tempo for castling rather than} 9... dxe4 $2 10. O-O $16) 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 dxe4 12. O-O (12. Nf4 Qd6 13. Bxe4 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f6]} 14. O-O Nf6 15. Bf3 O-O $11) (12. Ng5 Qb6 13. Nxe4 O-O 14. O-O-O Qxd4 15. Qf4 Nc6 $132) 12... Qd6 13. Bxe4 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7f6] (more flexible that castling at once)} 14. Qf4 (14. Rfe1 O-O) 14... Qxf4 15. Nxf4 Nf6 16. Bf3 Kd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7d6]} (16... O-O 17. Rac1 g5 18. Nh5 Nxh5 19. Bxh5 c6 {is also fine}) 17. Rfe1 Kd6 $11 {[%cal Gc7c6]}) (9. Nf3 Bb4+ $1 {is once again a useful intermezzo:} (9... f5 {seems premature because of} 10. O-O fxe4 (10... dxe4 $2 11. Ne5 {[%cal Gd3c4]} exd3 12. Re1 $18) 11. Qb3 $36) 10. Bd2 (10. Nfd2 {and only here comes} f5 $1 (10... dxe4 $6 11. O-O $36) 11. O-O (11. Qh5+ g6 12. Qh6 Bf8 13. Qh4 fxe4 14. O-O Qg4 $1 {The simplest - the queen has already done a good job and can be exchanged.} 15. Qxg4 Bxg4 {and now:} 16. f3 (16. Rae1 h6 $5 ({the calmer} 16... Kd7 {is likely to transpose to the line with 16.f3, see below}) 17. Bf6 Kf7 $1 18. Bxh8 exd3 19. Nf3 (19. f3 Bf5 20. g4 Bd7 21. Re3 Bb4 22. Rf2 Nc6 23. Be5 Nxe5 24. Rxe5 a5 25. Rxd5 Bc6 26. Re5 Rd8 $132) 19... Bxf3 20. gxf3 Nc6 21. Be5 Nxe5 22. Rxe5 Bd6 $44 23. Re3 (23. Rxd5 {is running into} a6 $1 {[%csl Rd5]} 24. Rd1 Ke6 25. Ra5 b5 26. Rxd3 Bb4 27. Re3+ Kd6 28. Raa3 Bxa3 29. Rxa3 Kd5 $11) 23... d2 24. Rd1 Bf4 25. Rxd2 Bxe3 26. fxe3 $11) 16... exd3 17. fxg4 Bd6 18. Rae1+ Kd7 19. Rf7+ Kc6 20. Nf3 (20. Re3 Na6 21. Rxd3 Raf8 $11) 20... Na6 21. Be7 {looks frightening, but the d3-pawn is still very alive and kicking, as illustrated by} Rae8 22. Rc1+ Kb6 23. Bxd6 cxd6 24. Rf6 Re2 25. Rxd6+ Ka5 26. Rxd5+ b5 $11) 11... fxe4 12. Re1 O-O 13. Qb3 Nc6 14. Rxe4 Qd6 {is a solid option, White has trouble with his d4-pawn, e.g.} ({Black has plenty of activity after} 14... Qg6 $5 15. Qxd5+ Kh8 16. Re3 (16. Nf3 Bf5 17. a3 Bd6 $132) 16... Bf5 17. Ne4 Rae8 $44 (17... Bd6 $5 18. a3 h6 19. Bh4 Bf4)) 15. a3 Ba5 16. Nf3 h6 17. Bh4 Be6 18. Re3 Rxf3 $1 19. gxf3 Nxd4 20. Qa4 (20. Qxb7 Rf8 21. Bg3 Qd7 $44) 20... Bb6 $44 21. Rae1 $140 Bd7 22. Qd1 Nc6 23. R3e2 Nd4 $11) 10... Bxd2+ 11. Nfxd2 dxe4 12. O-O Qd5 $1 ({White retains some typical initiative for positions with an isolated d4-pawn after} 12... O-O 13. Nxe4 $14 {The concrete answer in the text is almost sealing the fate of that pawn.}) 13. Bxe4 (13. Nxe4 Nc6 14. Rc1 $5 ({a serious practical try; White has compensation, but not more after} 14. Re1 O-O 15. Qf3 Qxd4 16. Ng5 {e.g.} g6 17. Re8 Bf5 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. Bxf5 Qxb2 20. Rb1 Qf6 21. Bxg6 Qxg6 22. Rxb7 Re8 $11) 14... O-O (14... Qxd4 $6 15. Ng5 $1 $36) 15. Rc4 Qd8 16. Nc3 (16. Qh5 h6 17. Rd1 Ne7 $11) 16... Ne7 17. Be4 Re8 $11) 13... Qxd4 14. Rc1 (14. Qh5 h6 15. Nf3 Qf6 16. Rac1 c6 17. Qc5 Be6 18. Rfe1 Nd7 19. Qb4 Rb8 20. Bc2 Qe7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8]}) (14. Qc2 h6 15. Rac1 O-O {will just transpose}) 14... O-O 15. Qc2 (15. Rxc7 Nc6 $11) 15... h6 16. Nf3 Qf6 17. Qxc7 Nc6 $11) 9... Be7 $1 (9... dxe4 $143 10. fxe4 Bb4+ 11. Kf2 $14 {[%cal Gg1f3]}) 10. Qd2 {One of the many options at White's disposal:} (10. h4 h6 11. Be3 O-O 12. Ne2 dxe4 13. fxe4 Bb4+ 14. Nc3 c5 15. d5 Qf6 16. Rc1 Nd7 $132) (10. Be3 f5 $132) (10. Bxe7 {makes Black's task easier -} Qxe7 11. Qb3 dxe4 12. fxe4 O-O 13. Nf3 Nc6 $11 {[%cal Gc8g4]}) (10. Qc1 {can be met by} h6 {, questioning Bg5:} 11. Bxe7 (11. Bf4 dxe4 12. fxe4 {and here Black can impetuously speed up his development without paying attention at the hanging c7-pawn, for example} Nc6 13. Nf3 Nb4 $1 14. Bb1 Qa6 $1 15. Kf2 (15. Qc3 f5 $1) 15... Bg4 16. Qc3 Rd8 $132) (11. Be3 {has protected the d4-pawn, but Black can go on in the same energetic manner -} dxe4 12. fxe4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4]} 13. Nf3 Nb4 $1 14. Bb1 Qa6 $1 15. Kf2 (15. Qxc7 Bd7 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 16. Qe5 Rc8 $44) 15... Bg4 16. Qxc7 Rc8 17. Qg3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 O-O 19. Rg1 g6 {and the active pieces seem to compensate the pawn -} 20. Kg2 Nc2 21. Bxc2 Rxc2+ 22. Kh1 Rfc8 $44) 11... Qxe7 12. Ne2 dxe4 13. fxe4 Bg4 {will challenge the central pawns again:} 14. O-O (14. Nf4 Nc6 15. O-O Qd6 16. d5 (16. Nd5 Be6 $11) 16... Ne5 $11) 14... Nc6 15. Qc3 Bxe2 16. Bxe2 Qxe4 17. Rxf7 O-O-O $1 (17... Kxf7 $2 18. Bc4+) 18. Bf3 Qxd4+ 19. Qxd4 Nxd4 20. Bg4+ Kb8 21. Rxg7 h5 $11) 10... Nc6 11. Ne2 dxe4 12. Bxe4 ({In case of} 12. fxe4 {the point behind 10....Nc6 is revealed by} Bb4 $1 13. Nc3 Nxd4 {The forced play continues with} 14. Bb5+ $1 Bd7 15. Qxd4 Bxc3+ 16. Qxc3 Bxb5 17. Qxg7 Rf8 $1 18. O-O-O f6 19. Bh4 (19. Bh6 Rg8 20. Qxh7 Qxa2 $132) 19... Qf7 20. Qh6 {and Black can finally get ready for castling to the long and ultimately equalize after} Bd7 $11 {[%cal Ge8c8]}) 12... O-O 13. d5 (13. O-O Bxg5 14. Qxg5 Qd6 15. Qc5 (15. Rfd1 Ne7 16. Qf4 Rd8 $11) 15... Rd8 16. Rac1 Nxd4 17. Qxd4 Qxd4+ 18. Nxd4 Rxd4 19. Rxc7 a5 20. Bxb7 Bxb7 21. Rxb7 h5 $44 {[%cal Gh5h4]}) 13... Bxg5 14. Qxg5 Qe7 15. Qe3 (15. h4 h6 {will most probably continue analogously to the next line with 15.Qxe7}) (15. Qxe7 Nxe7 16. Rc1 Rd8 17. Nf4 c6 18. dxc6 bxc6 19. O-O Bf5 20. Bxf5 Nxf5 $11) (15. Qd2 Rd8 16. O-O-O Nb4 17. Rhe1 ({leads to exchanges in the center and full equality; Black seems in order after} 17. Nc3 Qc5 18. Kb1 f5 19. Bc2 Nxc2 20. Qxc2 Bd7 $11 {as well}) 17... Qc5+ 18. Kb1 Nxd5 19. Nf4 c6 $11) 15... f5 $1 $132 16. dxc6 fxe4 17. O-O bxc6 18. Ng3 (18. fxe4 Rxf1+ 19. Rxf1 Qb4 20. b3 Ba6 $11) 18... Qb4 $1 {The final touch - Black will take the b2-pawn and compensate by this his wrecked queenside structure.} 19. Qxe4 Qxb2 20. Rfd1 h6 $11 *

