1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. Nf3 ({In reply to} 4. Ne2 {, besides transposing to the text, Black has} Nc6 $1 {and now:} 5. d5 (5. c3 d5 $1 {should comfortably equalize -} 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O exd4 ({an original idea is} 7... Bd6 $5 8. Be4 $140 Nde7) 8. cxd4 Be7 9. Re1 O-O 10. Nbc3 Bf6 11. Be4 Be6 $11) 5... Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d3]} 6. c4 a5 7. Nbc3 Nxd3+ 8. Qxd3 Be7 9. O-O O-O $11) (4. d5 {makes sense in combination with c2-c4, so Black must play accurately, namely} Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5]} ({less precise are both} 4... Be7 5. c4 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) ({and} 4... c6 5. c4 $14) 5. c4 {allows Black to exchange Bd3 after} (5. f3 Be7 6. c4 h5 $1 7. h4 ({in case of} 7. Nc3 {Black can go on with his dark-squared strategy by} h4 8. Nge2 Nh7 $5 {[%cal Ge7g5]} 9. O-O $140 Bg5 10. Bc2 Nhf8 $11 {[%cal Gf8g6]}) 7... c6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Be3 cxd5 10. cxd5 Nc5 11. Bc2 a5 {Both sides are prudently executing their plans, the position remains balanced after} 12. Nge2 Ne8 13. g3 Bd7 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 14. a4 Qb6 15. O-O Nc7 16. Qd2 N7a6 17. Nb5 Nb4 18. Nec3 Rac8 $11) (5. Be3 c6 6. c4 Nc5 7. Bxc5 ({the hunting after the bishops after} 7. Nc3 {can be realized by} Qb6 $1 8. Nge2 $140 Ng4 9. Bxc5 Qxc5 10. O-O Be7 $11) 7... dxc5 8. Nc3 Bd6 9. Nf3 O-O $11) 5... Nc5 6. Nc3 Nxd3+ 7. Qxd3 {and think about the thematic f7-f5 advance, for example} Be7 8. h3 (8. Nge2 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Ge7g5]}) 8... O-O 9. Be3 h6 $5 10. Nf3 (10. Nge2 Nd7 {[%cal Ge7g5]}) (10. g4 c6 11. Nge2 cxd5 12. cxd5 Nh7 $132) 10... c6 11. O-O cxd5 12. cxd5 Bd7 13. a4 Nh7 $11 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gh7g5]}) (4. c3 Nbd7 $5 (4... d5 {deserves attention as well -} 5. dxe5 Nxe4 6. Nf3 Nc5 7. Bc2 Bg4 8. O-O Nc6 $13 {with play in the spirit of the Open variation}) (4... Be7 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 O-O 7. O-O $14) 5. f4 (5. Nf3 d5 $1 6. Qe2 (6. dxe5 dxe4 7. exf6 exf3 $132) 6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 Qe7 (7... Be7 $5 {is an analogous to a kine in the Petroff pawn sacrifice in return for the pair of bishops -} 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Qd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7f5]} 11. O-O $140 Qf5 12. Nd2 a5 13. Re1 O-O 14. Qxf5 Bxf5 15. Nf3 c5 16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. Nxg5 Rad8 18. Rad1 h6 19. Nf3 Rfe8 $44) 8. dxe5 Nxe4 9. Qxe4 Nc5 10. Qd4 Qe6 {[%cal Ge6g6]} 11. O-O Qg6 $44 {is another version of the same idea}) (5. Qc2 d5 $5 (5... g6 {is a decent option, placing Bf8 on a more active position against the set-up with} 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O) 6. exd5 exd4 7. Nf3 Nxd5 8. O-O (8. Nxd4 Nc5 $11) 8... Be7 9. Nxd4 h6 (9... Nc5 10. Bf5) 10. Rd1 O-O 11. Nd2 Re8 12. N2f3 Bf8 $11) ({in reply to} 5. Ne2 {, which keeps the opportunity for f2-f4 open, Black's direct shot at equality is once again} d5 $5 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Be7 8. Nd2 O-O 9. Nc4 (9. Qc2 h6 $11) 9... exd4 10. Nxd4 Re8 $5 11. Qf3 (11. Bxh7+ Kxh7 12. Qh5+ Kg8 13. Qxd5 Nb6 14. Qxd8 Bxd8 15. Nxb6 axb6 16. Bf4 Bd7 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 17. Rfd1 c5 18. Nf3 Bc6 $44) (11. Re1 Bc5 $11) 11... N7f6 12. h3 (12. Nf5 Bf8) 12... Bc5 $11) 5... Be7 6. Nd2 $5 $146 (6. Nf3 d5 $1 7. Nxe5 (7. fxe5 dxe4 8. exf6 Nxf6 $132) 7... dxe4 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O c5 $11) (6. Nh3 c5 $5 (6... O-O {looks normal}) 7. dxe5 ({in case of} 7. fxe5 $6 dxe5 8. d5 c4 9. Bc2 {, as in M. Aditya - Yu Yangyi, Ankara, 2024, I would prefer Black after the natural} b5 $15) 7... dxe5 8. Qe2 exf4 ({a concrete, though a bit risky regrouping: Black has also time for the prophylactic} 8... a6 $5) 9. Bxf4 Nf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8g6]} 10. Bb5+ N6d7 $1 (10... Bd7 $2 11. Na3 $16) 11. e5 ({Black will be fine, as soon as he chases Bb5 and liberates hinself of the pin along the d-file, in the line} 11. Na3 Ng6 12. O-O-O O-O 13. e5 Qc7 $132) 11... a6 12. Ba4 Ng6 13. e6 fxe6 14. Nd2 b5 15. Bc2 O-O $132) (6. Ne2 c5 $5 ({here Black should wait with} 6... O-O {because of} 7. Ng3 $1 {, overprotecting the e4-pawn}) 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 (8. a4 Re8 $132) 8... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} 9. Be3 Bb7 10. Ng3 {Here, when White can consider an exchange on e5, followed by d4-d5, it is time for} cxd4 11. cxd4 $140 exd4 12. Bxd4 Nc5 13. Nc3 Ne6 14. Bf2 (14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Qd2 Rc8 $11) 14... Nxf4 15. Nf5 Bc8 $1 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Bh4 Qe5 18. Bc2 N6h5 19. Qd2 Ng6 $132) 6... O-O {A reasonable decision before striking at the center:} (6... c5 $143 7. fxe5 dxe5 8. d5 $14) (6... exd4 7. cxd4 c5 8. d5 {must be also an achievement for White, as Nd7 is not usually seen in the Benoni structures; here it can be activated with ana arguable pawn sacrifice like} c4 9. Bxc4 Nc5 10. Qe2 O-O 11. Ngf3 a6 12. O-O b5 13. Bd3 $14) 7. Nh3 (7. Ne2 exd4 $1 8. cxd4 c5 9. d5 (9. O-O cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nc5 $11) 9... c4 $1 {is more justified here, e.g.} 10. Bb1 (10. Nxc4 Nc5 11. Nc3 b5 $132) 10... Nc5 11. O-O b5 $132) 7... c5 (7... Nb6 8. O-O Bxh3 9. gxh3 $13) 8. fxe5 dxe5 9. d5 Nb6 $1 10. Nf2 (10. c4 Bg4 11. Qc2 Bxh3 12. gxh3 Qd7 $132) 10... c4 $1 11. Bxc4 (11. Nxc4 Nxc4 12. Bxc4 Bc5 {[%csl Gc5]} 13. Qe2 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 Ng4+ 15. Ke1 f5 $132) 11... Nxc4 12. Nxc4 Bc5 {looks like a promise for a long-term compensation:} 13. Ne3 ({it is important that} 13. Be3 {is running into} Nxe4 $1 14. Bxc5 ({definitely not} 14. Nxe4 $2 Qh4+ $17) 14... Nxc5 15. O-O Nd7 16. Re1 f6 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6]}) 13... Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8d6]} 14. g4 (14. O-O Nd6 $44 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 14... Nd6 15. Qf3 a5 16. Bd2 (16. Nd3 Qh4+ 17. Qf2 Qxf2+ 18. Nxf2 a4 $44) 16... Bd7 17. O-O-O a4 $44) 4... exd4 $5 ({The insertion of} 4... Nbd7 5. c4 {before} g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. d5 Nc5 8. Bc2 a5 9. O-O O-O {seems to lead to a typical for KID situation, White has the promising} 10. a3 $14) (4... Nc6 {is fully playable, for instance} 5. d5 (5. c3 d5) 5... Nb4 6. Be2 a5 $132) 5. Nxd4 g6 ({In the view of the possible c2-c4 the alternative} 5... Be7 {is a bit passive, e.g.} 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 Nc6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Nc3 $14) 6. O-O Bg7 7. Nc3 (7. c4 {can be met by} Nc6 $1 8. Nxc6 $140 bxc6 9. Nc3 Rb8 10. Rb1 O-O 11. b3 Ng4 $132 {[%cal Gd8h4,Gg7e5,Gg4e5]}) 7... O-O 8. Bg5 (8. Bf4 {allows the immediate strike} d5 $5 9. exd5 (9. e5 $2 Nh5 $17) (9. Ndb5 Na6) 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. c3 (11. Nb5 Na6) 11... Bxd4 $1 12. cxd4 Nc6 $1 ({Black must reckon with the enemy bishops after} 12... Qxd4 {, instead, he can speed up his development and regain the central pawn with interest}) 13. Bxc7 Be6 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd5d4]}) (8. f4 c6 9. Kh1 Re8 $132) (8. Re1 Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. h3 Rb8 11. Rb1 {can invite the common tactical trick} Ng4 $1 12. hxg4 $140 (12. Bd2 Ne5 $11) 12... Bxc3 13. Bh6 Bxe1 14. Qxe1 {and here the simplest reaction is to take the c3-square away from Qe1 by} Qf6 $11) (8. h3 a6 $5 (8... Nc6 {is possible again}) 9. a4 b6 10. Re1 Bb7 11. Bf4 Nbd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gf8e8]}) 8... h6 9. Bh4 c6 10. a4 {A natural desire to stop the counterplay with b7-b5.} (10. Re1 Qb6 $1 11. Nb3 a5 12. Na4 Qa7 13. c4 Nbd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5]}) (10. Kh1 b5 11. f4 Qc7 {is a typical situation, which must be studied thoroughly:} 12. Qd2 (12. Qf3 a6 13. Rae1 Nbd7 14. Bxf6 ({the direct} 14. e5 {does not achieve much after} dxe5 15. Qxc6 Qxc6 16. Nxc6 exf4 17. Ne7+ Kh8 18. Bxg6 fxg6 19. Nxg6+ Kg8 20. Nxf8 Nxf8 21. Rxf4 Nh5 $11) 14... Nxf6 15. e5 dxe5 16. fxe5 Ng4 {and now:} 17. Qxc6 (17. Nxc6 Be6 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Rac8 20. Bxg6 (20. Rf4 {seems to lead to an inevitable draw after} Qxc6 21. Qxc6 Nf2+ 22. Rxf2 Rxc6 23. b3 Re6 $11) 20... Qxc6 21. Bxf7+ Kh7 22. Qxc6 Rxc6 23. e6 Nf6 24. e7 Rxf7 25. e8=Q Nxe8 26. Rxf7 Rxc2 $11) 17... Qxc6 18. Nxc6 Kh8 $1 19. h3 (19. Be4 Bd7) 19... Bd7 20. Be4 Rac8 21. Na7 Rc7 22. Naxb5 axb5 23. hxg4 Bxe5 ({if Black is not satisfied with the text, then he can opt for} 23... Rc5) ({or, probably his best,} 23... Ra7 24. Bd3 $140 b4 25. Nb5 Bxb5 26. Bxb5 Rxa2 27. Bc4 Ra5 28. Bxf7 Bxe5 29. Bxg6 Rxf1+ 30. Rxf1 Bxb2 $11) 24. Nd5 Ra7 25. Bxg6 Bxb2 26. Re7 Bd4 27. Rfxf7 Rxf7 28. Rxf7 (28. Bxf7 $6 Bc5 $11) 28... Be6 29. Rxa7 Bxa7 30. Nc7 Bxa2 31. Nxb5 Bb8 {[%cal Gh8g7,Gg7f6] with decent chances to hold due to the limited material}) (12. Qe1 b4 13. e5 (13. Nce2 Nbd7 14. Qxb4 c5 15. Nb5 Qc6 $132) (13. Na4 a5 $132) 13... dxe5 14. fxe5 Ng4 15. Ne4 Nd7 $1 16. Qg3 Qxe5 17. Qxg4 Qxd4 18. Be7 f5 19. Qxg6 Ne5 20. Nf6+ (20. Qd6 Nxd3 21. Qxd4 Bxd4 22. Bxf8 fxe4 23. cxd3 c5 $132 {[%cal Gc8a6]}) 20... Rxf6 21. Qe8+ Kh7 22. Bxf6 Bxf6 23. Bxf5+ Bxf5 24. Qxa8 Be4 $1 (24... Bh3 $144 $1 {, when White must again reconcile himself with the perpetual}) 25. Rxf6 Bxg2+ 26. Kxg2 Qg4+ 27. Kf2 Qd4+ $11) 12... Nbd7 13. Rae1 Bb7 14. a3 (14. Nf3 b4 15. Nd1 c5 16. e5 dxe5 17. fxe5 Ng4 18. e6 Nde5 $132) 14... Rae8 15. Nf3 a6 16. e5 dxe5 17. fxe5 Nh5 18. e6 Rxe6 19. Rxe6 fxe6 20. Bxg6 Nf4 21. Bg3 (21. Be4 Nc5 $132) 21... e5 22. Bxf4 (22. Be4 Nc5 $11) 22... exf4 {and Black must be able to neutralize} 23. Re1 {with the help of} Ne5 24. Nxe5 Bxe5 $11) 10... Re8 (10... a5 $143 11. Nb3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 11. a5 (11. Re1 a5 12. Bf1 Qb6 $132) ({An analogous line to the main one is going on with} 11. h3 d5 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Bb5 Bd7 14. Bxf6 (14. Nxd5 g5 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Bg3 Qxd4 17. Qxd4 Bxd4 18. Bxd7 Nxd7 19. Rad1 Bxb2 20. Rxd7 {is almost the same as the one with 14.Bxd7 to the leading text, in which the a-pawn is already on the 5th rank, while here} b6 $11 {is safe enough}) 14... Qxf6 15. Bxd7 Nxd7 16. Ndb5 Red8 17. Nc7 Rac8 18. N7xd5 Qe6 {and the long-ranged Bg7 is yielding counterplay, e.g.} 19. Qg4 (19. Qe1 Ne5 $44) 19... Qxg4 20. hxg4 Re8 21. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1 Kf8 $44 {[%cal Gc8c4]}) (11. Nb3 Na6 {demonstrates that Black can exploit the b4-square without a7-a5.} 12. h3 (12. f4 Bg4 $1 13. Qc1 Nb4 14. a5 b5 15. h3 Nxd3 16. cxd3 Bd7 $11) 12... d5 $1 13. Bxa6 (13. exd5 Nb4 14. dxc6 bxc6 $44) 13... bxa6 14. f4 Qc7 15. e5 Nh5 16. Ne2 g5 $132 17. fxg5 hxg5 18. Ned4 (18. Ng3 Nxg3 19. Bxg3 Bxe5 20. Bxe5 Qxe5 $11) 18... gxh4 19. Qxh5 Rxe5 20. Qxh4 {and here he can rely on his powerful bishops after} c5 21. Nf3 Re6 $44) 11... d5 $1 {A start of a long forced line to equality, which is full of tactical subtleties.} ({An alternative plan is} 11... b5 $5 12. axb6 Qxb6 13. Nb3 Nbd7 $13) 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Bb5 (13. Re1 Rxe1+ 14. Qxe1 Nc6 $11) 13... Bd7 14. Bxf6 {This is how White can win the central pawn.} ({In case of} 14. Bxd7 Nbxd7 15. Nxd5 g5 {Black is solving his problems by force -} 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Bg3 Qxd4 18. Qxd4 Bxd4 19. Rad1 Bxb2 20. Rxd7 Bc3 21. f4 g4 $1 22. Rb1 {and here the most practical continuation is} Red8 $1 23. Rdxb7 $140 Bxa5 24. Bf2 Rdc8 $11) 14... Qxf6 15. Bxd7 Nxd7 16. Ndb5 Red8 17. Qxd5 (17. Nxd5 Qxb2 18. Rb1 Qa2 $11) 17... Ne5 18. Qxb7 (18. Qb3 Qc6 19. Rfd1 Nc4 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Nxa7 Qc5 $44) 18... a6 19. Nd5 (19. Ne4 Qc6 20. Qxc6 Nxc6 21. Nbc3 Rab8 $44) (19. Nc7 Rab8 20. Qxa6 Qxa6 21. Nxa6 Rxb2 22. Ra2 Rxa2 23. Nxa2 Nc6 24. N2b4 Nxa5 25. g3 Rd2 $11 {[%cal Gg7d4,Ga5c4]}) 19... Nf3+ $1 20. Kh1 (20. gxf3 Qg5+ 21. Kh1 Rab8 $132) 20... Qxb2 21. Rab1 ({White does not profit from} 21. Ne7+ Kh7 22. Qxf3 axb5 23. Qxf7 {, for after the forced} Qf6 24. Qxf6 Bxf6 25. Rae1 {the accurate} Rd6 $1 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ga8a5] is arresting the knight. Indeed, White is able to save it by means of} 26. f4 Rxa5 27. f5 g5 $11 {, but it is not realistic to play for a win.}) 21... Qe5 22. gxf3 Rab8 23. Ne7+ Kh7 24. Qe4 {White's best bet.} (24. Qc7 Qh5 25. Qf4 Rxb5 26. Rxb5 Qxb5 27. c4 Qxa5 28. Qxf7 Qh5 29. Nd5 Qh3 30. Rg1 g5 31. Nf6+ Kh8 32. Nh5 Be5 33. Ng3 Bxg3 34. Qf6+ Kh7 35. Rxg3 Rd1+ 36. Rg1 Rd3 $11) 24... Qc5 25. Na7 $5 {A tricky moves - due to the various forks this knight is indirectly protected.} ({An exceptionally beautiful line is} 25. Nc6 Re8 26. Nxb8 Rxe4 27. Nxa6 Qxc2 28. fxe4 {and here comes the stunning} Qe2 $3 $11 {[%cal Ge2f3] and White cannot prevent the perpetual!}) (25. Rg1 Re8 26. Rbe1 axb5 $11) 25... Rxb1 26. Rxb1 Qxf2 $1 27. Qf4 Rd2 28. Rg1 Re2 $1 {The final saving nuance!} 29. Nac6 Re1 $1 30. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 31. Kg2 Qe2+ 32. Kh3 Qf1+ $13 *

