1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 e5 {This is the consistent move.} (3... g6 {will shift to} 4. Nc3 {(the Pirc)} ({or} 4. c4 {(the Saemisch KID)})) 4. d5 {Insisting on building a solid central pawn chain rather than:} ({The exchanges} 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {should not disturb Black:} 6. Bc4 (6. Be3 Be6 (6... Nbd7 {is a sound alternative, as, besides transposing to 6.Bc4 below, Black is able to neutralize} 7. Bc4 {by tactical means, namely} Bb4+ $1 8. Nd2 $140 Ke7 {[%cal Gb4c5]}) 7. Nd2 Nfd7 {[%cal Gf8c5]} 8. Bc4 Bxc4 9. Nxc4 b5 10. Nd2 (10. Na5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Bxa5 12. Bxa5 Nc6 $11 {[%cal Gd8e7]}) 10... Bc5 11. Kf2 (11. Nf1 a5 $11 {[%cal Gb8a6]}) 11... Bxe3+ 12. Kxe3 Nc6 $11) 6... Ke8 7. Be3 (7. Nc3 c6 8. a4 a5 9. Be3 Na6 $11) (7. a3 c6 8. h4 a5 9. Nh3 b5 10. Ba2 Na6 11. Nf2 Nc5 $11) 7... Nbd7 {is reaching the aforementioned transposition, the position is balanced, e.g.} 8. Nd2 (8. Nc3 c6 9. a4 a5 $11 {[%cal Gf8c5]}) 8... Bc5 9. Nf1 a5 $11 {[%cal Ge8e7,Gc7c6]}) (4. Ne2 {looks flexible, but Black has a curious way to use the early f2-f3 by playing} exd4 5. Nxd4 d5 $1 6. e5 Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gd8h4,Gc7c5]} (6... Nfd7 $6 7. f4 $14) 7. g3 (7. Qd2 $6 g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 $15 {[%cal Gc7c5]}) 7... c5 ({more forcing than} 7... g6 $5 {, which is a good alternative with a probable transposition to the lines after 8....d4 below}) 8. Nb5 (8. Nb3 $6 Nc6 9. f4 g6 $15 {[%csl Rb3]}) 8... d4 {prevents the occasional tactical opportunity from above, in the ensuing original positions Black''s chances are not worse, for example:} (8... a6 {seems to equalize in spite of White's courageous try to gain material by} 9. Qxd5 $5 (9. N5a3 Nc6 10. f4 g6 11. Bg2 Be6 $132) 9... axb5 10. Bxb5+ Nc6 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. g4 Be7 {The extra piece cannot be saved, but the powerful bishops are entering the game.} 14. gxh5 Bh4+ 15. Kf1 ({so is with Black's rooks in case of} 15. Ke2 Re8 16. Bf4 Ra4 $11) 15... Bh3+ 16. Ke2 Re8 17. Bf4 Bf6 18. Kf2 Bxe5 19. Bxe5 Rxe5 20. h6 g6 21. Kg3 (21. Nd2 Rg5 22. Rhg1 Rh5 $11) 21... Bf5 22. Rc1 {and here} Bd7 {[%cal Ge5g5] seals the fate of the h5-pawn, e.g.} 23. h4 g5 24. Nc3 gxh4+ 25. Kxh4 Re6 $11) 9. f4 (9. Nd2 a6 10. Na3 Nc6 11. Qe2 Be7 12. f4 g6 13. Bg2 O-O ({a sound alternaive is} 13... Ng7 14. Nac4 h5 $11 {, as mentioned below}) 14. O-O f5 $11) 9... g6 10. Nd2 a6 11. Na3 Be7 12. Bg2 {is about to transpose, there is also} Ng7 13. Nac4 h5 14. Ne4 Nf5 15. O-O Nc6 16. b3 Be6 $11) (4. Be3 $6 exd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd2 d5 $15) 4... Be7 (4... c6 {is less accurate in the view of} 5. c4 Be7 6. Nc3 $14) 5. Be3 ({In case of} 5. c4 {Black's move order will be justified by the subtle} Nfd7 $1 (5... a5 $144) 6. Be3 a5 {[%cal Gb8a6]} 7. Nc3 Na6 {[%cal Ge8g8]} 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 (9. a3 Nac5 10. Bc2 c6 11. Nge2 Nb6 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Qd3 Bg5 $132) 9... Nb4 10. a3 (10. Bb1 Nb6 $1 11. Bxb6 ({Black has a promising play on the dark squares after} 11. b3 Bh4+ $1 12. g3 Bg5 $132 {as well}) 11... cxb6 12. Nb5 Bg5 13. Nec3 Qf6 $132) ({a modest retreat like} 10. Bf2 {can inspire Black to seize space on the queenside by} a4 11. a3 $140 (11. Bb1 a3 $132) 11... Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 b6 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 13. O-O-O f5 14. exf5 Nc5 15. Bxc5 Bxf5 16. Ne4 bxc5 17. N2c3 Qb8 $11) {is probably White's best, with similar scenario after} 10... Nxd3+ 11. Qxd3 b6 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gf7f5]}) (5. Ne2 $5 {is a very rare, but interesting move order from White, which can provoke an original reaction like} b5 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc7c6]} ({other, more routine, options are} 5... c6 6. c4 O-O 7. Be3 a6 8. Nbc3) ({and} 5... O-O 6. Be3 {with likely transpositions}) 6. c4 {must be deservedly considered the acid test for the bold thrust:} (6. a3 {[%cal Gb1c3] looks too humble to pose problems, but the play can become very complex -} c6 7. Nbc3 O-O 8. Be3 a6 9. g4 $5 {and here} cxd5 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Qc7 12. Qxa8 Nc6 {can result in an unexpected draw by repetition after} 13. Nc3 Bh4+ 14. Kd2 Bb7 15. Nd5 Qd7 {, as White does not need to deviate from} 16. Nb6 Qc7 17. Nd5 Qd7 $11) (6. Ng3 c6 7. c4 (7. dxc6 $6 a6 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 7... h5 $1 8. h4 O-O $132) (6. Be3 c6 7. c4 {- 5.Be3}) 6... bxc4 ({in comparison to the leading text with 5.Be3, here} 6... c6 $2 {is less justified, as revealed by} 7. cxb5 cxd5 8. exd5 Bb7 9. Nbc3 Nbd7 10. a4 $16) (6... O-O {is an option -} 7. Be3 (7. cxb5 a6 8. Qa4 Bb7 9. Nbc3 axb5 10. Qxb5 Ba6 11. Qb3 c6 $44) 7... bxc4 8. Nec3 c6 9. Bxc4 {is reaching the main line below}) 7. Nec3 O-O 8. Bxc4 c6 9. Be3 {Here is the mentioned transposition from above, Black must continue his fight for the initiative by} Ba6 $1 (9... cxd5 10. Nxd5 Nbd7 11. Nbc3 $14) 10. Na3 (10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. dxc6 Nb4 12. O-O Nxc6 $11) (10. Nd2 $144 cxd5 11. Nxd5 Bxc4 12. Nxc4) 10... cxd5 {and now:} 11. Nxd5 (11. exd5 Qa5 12. Qd3 (12. O-O Nbd7) 12... Rc8 13. O-O Bb7 14. Rfd1 Na6 $11) 11... Bxc4 12. Nxc4 (12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Nxc4 {tends to confuse Black, but his play in this variation is rarely linked with passively defending the backward d6-pawn, so} Nc6 $1 {, aiming at a splendid d4-square, is the principled answer.} 14. Qxd6 (14. O-O Nd4 $11) ({or} 14. Nxd6 Qc7 15. Nc4 Rfd8 16. Qa4 Nd4 17. Kf2 a5 18. Rhd1 {, when} h6 $5 {[%cal Gf6g5] is a remarkable idea for establishing Nd4 by trading the dark-squared bishops, for instance} 19. Rac1 Bg5 20. Bxg5 hxg5 $44 {[%csl Gd4]}) 14... Qc8 15. O-O ({Black can claim a typical compensattion after} 15. Qd3 Rd8 16. Qc3 Nd4 17. b3 Bh4+ 18. Bf2 Bxf2+ 19. Kxf2 a5 {as well, e.g.} 20. Rhc1 Qe6 21. Ne3 a4 22. b4 Rac8 23. Qb2 h5 $44 {[%csl Gd4]}) 15... Nd4 (15... Rd8 $6 16. Qa3 Nd4 17. Qa4 $14) 16. Bxd4 exd4 17. Rac1 Rd8 18. Qa3 (18. Qf4 Qa6 19. e5 Be7 $44) 18... d3 19. e5 (19. Ne5 Qe6 20. Nxd3 {has gotten rid of the passed pawn, but Black can regain one of the pawns after} Be7 21. Qc3 Rac8 22. Qd2 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Qb6+ 24. Kh1 Qa6 25. Rd1 Qxa2 {with probable full annihilation of the queenside.} 26. Qc3 h5 $44) 19... Qe6 $1 20. exf6 (20. Qc3 Be7 $44) 20... d2 {The tactical justification of Black's previous moves.} 21. Nxd2 (21. Rcd1 Qxc4 22. Qe3 gxf6 23. Rxd2 Rxd2 24. Qxd2 Qxa2 $11) 21... Rxd2 22. Qb4 (22. Rce1 Qb6+ 23. Kh1 Qxb2 24. Qxa7 Qxa2 $11) 22... Qe3+ 23. Kh1 gxf6 (23... Qg5 $5 24. Rg1 Rad8 25. fxg7 Rxg2 $2 26. Qc4 Rxg1+ 27. Rxg1 Qd2 $44) 24. Rce1 Qg5 25. Rg1 Rad8 $44) 12... Nxd5 {leaves White with an analogous choice:} 13. Qxd5 {is pretending for more, Black should fight for the d5-height by} (13. exd5 {is again less principled, it is also providing Black with} Bh4+ $5 14. g3 f5 $1 {[%cal Gf5f4]} 15. O-O (15. Qd3 f4 16. Bf2 Bg5 17. Kf1 fxg3 18. hxg3 h6 19. Kg2 Qc7 $11) 15... f4 16. Bxf4 (16. Bf2 Bg5 $11) 16... exf4 17. gxh4 Nd7 18. Qd4 (18. Kh1 Nb6 $44) 18... Nb6 (18... Qxh4 19. Nxd6 Qh5 $44 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gd7f6]}) 19. Nxb6 axb6 $44) 13... Na6 $1 $132 (13... Nd7 $143 $6 14. O-O Nf6 15. Qb7 $1 Rc8 16. Rac1 Rc7 17. Qb5 $14) 14. a3 {takes the b4-square away from Na6, so} (14. O-O Nb4 $1 15. Qd2 d5 $1 16. Nxe5 Qd6 17. Nd3 dxe4 18. Nxb4 Qxb4 19. Qxb4 Bxb4 20. a3 Bd6 21. Rad1 (21. fxe4 Be5) 21... Be5 22. b4 Rfc8 $11 {[%cal Gc8c3]}) (14. Qb7 Qc8 $1 {equalizes by force, as illustrated by} 15. Qxc8 Rfxc8 16. b3 Nb4 17. Ke2 d5 18. exd5 Nxd5 $11) 14... Nc7 {and now:} 15. Qa5 (15. Qd2 d5 16. Nxe5 Qd6 17. Ng4 (17. Bf4 Qa6 18. Qe2 Qa5+ 19. Qd2 Qb5 $44 {/=}) 17... Rfd8 18. O-O Qe6 19. Qa5 Ne8 $44) 15... Bh4+ 16. g3 (16. Ke2 f5 $1 17. exf5 $140 Rxf5 18. Rhd1 d5 19. Rac1 h5 $1 20. g3 Be7 21. Rd3 Rb8 $132) 16... Bg5 17. Bf2 ({a reasonable decision to keep this bishop, as} 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 {will be much more to Black's taste, as demonstrated by the sound pawn sacrifice} 18. O-O Ne6 $1 19. Nxd6 Nd4 $44 {[%csl Gd4]}) 17... Rc8 18. Rd1 (18. O-O Ne6 19. Qd5 Rc7 20. Rad1 Qf6 $11) 18... Ne6 19. Qxd8 Rfxd8 {The trade of the queens has brought the game into a new phase. Indeed, it is not a luxury to have a pawn as the one on d6, but it is equally diffivult for White to find the key to it.} 20. b3 (20. Nxd6 $2 Rc6 $17) 20... Rc7 $1 {This rook ia waiting for its star moment along the c-file:} 21. h4 (21. Rd3 h5 {is not just an ordinary kingside expansion - by it Black is creating conditions for a counterstrike with f7-f5.} 22. Kd1 $5 {[%cal Gd1c2]} (22. Ke2 h4 23. Rhd1 Rb8 $11) 22... g6 23. Re1 Be7 24. Re2 Rdc8 $11 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 21... Bf6 (21... Be7 $143 22. Ne3 {and Rc7 cannot penetrate}) 22. Ke2 h5 $11) 5... c6 $1 6. c4 b5 $1 {A very important plan of initiating active counterplay striaght in the opening!} (6... O-O 7. Nc3 $14) 7. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2c3] A very characteristic plan in such Saemitsch structure - this knight goes to the c3-square and leaves a large choice of routes in front of the other one.} (7. Nc3 b4 8. Na4 O-O 9. Qd2 Na6 10. Bd3 Bd7 $132 {[%csl Ra4]}) (7. a3 O-O (7... bxc4 $144 8. Bxc4 O-O) 8. Nc3 bxc4 9. Bxc4 cxd5 ({by inserting this exchange Black assures his Bc8 of the e6-square, though} 9... Bb7 {looks fine as well -} 10. Nge2 Nbd7 11. dxc6 Bxc6 {and the game Lupulescu - Kempinski, Germany, 2016, finissged in a draw 10 moves later}) 10. Nxd5 Be6 11. Ne2 Nbd7 $11) (7. dxc6 b4 $5 {[%cal Gb8c6]} (7... bxc4 8. Bxc4 Nxc6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Nge2 Be6 $11) 8. Qa4 Qc7 9. a3 (9. Qxb4 $2 d5 $19) 9... bxa3 10. Nxa3 Nxc6 11. Ne2 O-O 12. Nc3 Qb7 $132) ({Accepting the pawn by} 7. cxb5 cxd5 8. exd5 {is a principled continuation.} Bb7 9. Nc3 (9. Bc4 $144 Nbd7) 9... Nbd7 10. Bc4 ({for details about} 10. a4 Nb6 11. Bxb6 Qxb6 12. Bc4 {see 12.a4 below}) 10... Nb6 {is arriving at important crossroads:} 11. Bxb6 {is more reasonable, even though the a7-g1 diagonal is exposed.} (11. Bb3 a6 12. bxa6 Rxa6 $132 {[%cal Gd8a8]}) ({the trade of the main defender of the d5-pawn after} 11. Qd3 Nxc4 12. Qxc4 {should suit Black, he can prove compensation by means of} Rc8 $5 ({or} 12... a6 $5 13. Nge2 Qa5 $44) 13. Qd3 Qa5 14. Kf2 Rxc3 $1 15. Qxc3 Qxb5 16. Qb3 Qxb3 17. axb3 a6 $44 {[%cal Gf6d5]}) 11... Qxb6 12. a4 {is anyway a move White cannot do without:} (12. Nge2 O-O 13. a4 a6 14. bxa6 (14. a5 $6 Qc5) 14... Bxa6 15. Bxa6 Qxa6 16. Nb5 Qb6 17. Nec3 Rfc8 $44) 12... Rc8 ({worth checking is} 12... Qd4 $5 13. Qxd4 exd4 14. Nce2 Rc8 15. b3 Bxd5 16. Bxd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd4 Kd7 18. Nge2 Rhe8 19. Kf2 (19. O-O Bg5 $44) 19... Bh4+ 20. g3 Bd8 $44) 13. b3 (13. Bb3 {is naturally met by} a6 {and Black's prospects are not worse, for example} 14. a5 Qe3+ 15. Nge2 axb5 16. Qd2 (16. a6 Ba8) 16... Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 b4 18. Na2 Nxd5 19. a6 Bc6 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Nxb4 Ba8 22. a7 Kd7 $132) 13... a5 $1 ({a subtle intermezzo;} 13... Qa5 14. Nge2 Bxd5 {regains the pawn, but the initiative is passing into White's hands -} 15. Bxd5 Rxc3 16. O-O $14) 14. bxa6 (14. Nge2 $6 O-O 15. Qd2 Nd7 $15 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gd7c5]}) 14... Bxa6 15. Bxa6 Qxa6 {with a typical for the Benko counterplay -} 16. Nge2 O-O 17. O-O Rc5 18. Kh1 (18. b4 Rc4 19. b5 Qa5 20. Qd2 Nd7 $44 {[%cal Gd7b6]}) 18... Rb8 19. Ne4 Rcc8 20. N2g3 g6 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. Ne4 Be7 $44) 7... bxc4 8. Nec3 Bb7 9. Bxc4 ({The immediate} 9. dxc6 {is providing Black with} Nxc6 10. Bxc4 Rc8 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc6d4]}) (9. Na3 {can bring trouble with the center after} cxd5 10. exd5 O-O 11. Nxc4 Na6 $132 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ga8c8,Ga6c7]}) 9... Nbd7 10. dxc6 ({Nothing is achieved by} 10. O-O Nb6 11. Bb3 cxd5 12. exd5 Ba6 13. Rf2 O-O $11) (10. a4 {is hardly an improvement either -} cxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Bxd5 13. Qxd5 Rb8 14. O-O Rxb2 15. Nc3 O-O 16. Bxa7 Qc7 17. Nb5 Qc2 18. Rf2 Rb1+ 19. Rxb1 Qxb1+ 20. Rf1 Qb4 21. Qb7 Rd8 22. Bb6 (22. Ra1 {will just repeat after} Qb2 $11) 22... Nxb6 23. Qxe7 Qc5+ 24. Kh1 Rf8 {and it is time to sign a draw agreement after} 25. Nxd6 Nxa4 $11) 10... Bxc6 11. Bb3 $1 {Thee first one of several useful prophylactic moves in a row.} ({Black does not experience problems after} 11. O-O Nb6 12. Nd2 d5 $11) ({or} 11. Qd3 O-O 12. Nd2 Rb8 13. O-O Nb6 $11) 11... a5 12. O-O Nb6 13. Kh1 $1 O-O 14. Na3 a4 15. Nc4 {A clever imtermediate move for preserving the control over the d5-spot, though Black has his own thoughts about it.} (15. Bxb6 {does not win a pawn -} Qxb6 16. Nxa4 (16. Bxa4 Bxa4 17. Nxa4 Qb4 18. Nc3 Qxb2 19. Nab5 Qb4 $11) 16... Bxa4 17. Bxa4 