1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. d5 {Below various options, with an exception of those, in which Ng1 is protecting the d4-pawn, are mentioned in brief - as a rule, Black obtains enough counterplay by taking it at once. The textmove is taking this pawn away, but, as soon as it cannot be supported by the one on c2, such advance (known are opening lines, in which Black is deliberately provoking it by sacrificing two tempi with Nb8-c6) should not confuse hte second player as well.} (4. g3 exd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 (6. Qd2 Qe7 7. Qe2 d5 $132) 6... Bg4 7. Be2 (7. f3 Be6 {[%cal Gd6d5]}) 7... Be6 (7... Bxe2 8. Qxe2 g6 $11 {[%cal Gf8g7]}) 8. Bf3 Qd7 9. Nge2 O-O-O 10. Nf4 Bg4 $11) (4. h3 exd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 {is on the verge of different transpositions:} 6. Qd1 {is logically met by} (6. Qd3 {is practically transposing to the Central game (1.e4 e5 2.d4 exd4 3.Qxd4 Nc6 4.Qd3!? Nf6 5.Nc3), where the extra move h2-h3 is of little use. Black's most convincing way to equality remains the same, as follows -} d5 $1 7. Bf4 (7. exd5 Nb4 8. Qe2+ Qe7 $11 {[%cal Gb4d5]}) 7... d4 8. Nb5 Bb4+ 9. c3 dxc3 10. Qxd8+ (10. bxc3 $144 Ba5) 10... Kxd8 11. bxc3 (11. Bxc7+ Ke7 12. bxc3 Bc5 $11 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gf6e4]}) 11... Ba5 12. O-O-O+ Bd7 13. f3 a6 {This attack at the shaky Nb5 is leading to a surprising draw by repetition after} 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. cxd4 Ba4 16. Rd3 Bb5 $11) (6. Qe3 {has also to do with the Central game - the pawn on d6 stops the usual Bf8-b4, but Black has another equalizer in the view of} Be7 7. Bd2 $140 d5 $1 (7... O-O $143 8. O-O-O) 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Qe4 Nf6 $11) (6. Bb5 {is almost transposing to the Steinitz defense in the Ruy Lopez, raising again the question of how useful h2-h3 is.} Be7 $1 ({more precise than} 6... Bd7 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Nge2 $14) 7. Nf3 (7. Nge2 O-O 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Re8 $11) 7... O-O 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O c5 10. Qd3 a5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 11. Re1 Ba6 12. Qd1 Re8 13. Bf4 Nd7 14. e5 Nb6 $11) 6... Be6 $1 $146 {[%cal Gd6d5]} ({by both} 6... Be7 7. Nge2 O-O 8. g4 $36) ({and} 6... g6 7. g4 Bg7 8. Bg2 $14 {Black does not fight for the key d5-square}) 7. Nf3 (7. Nge2 d5 $11) (7. Bb5 d5 8. e5 Ne4 9. Nge2 (9. Nf3 Bb4 10. Bd2 a5 $11) 9... Bc5 10. O-O Nxc3 (10... O-O {is perfectly playable as well}) 11. Nxc3 Qd7 $11) 7... d5 8. e5 Ne4 9. Bd3 a6 $5 {is an unusual pawn sacrifice -} (9... f5 {is a reliable option in the spirit of the Open variation -} 10. exf6 (10. O-O Bc5 11. Bb5 O-O 12. Ne2 a5 13. c3 Bb6 14. Nfd4 Bd7 $11) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 (11. f7+ Bxf7 12. bxc3 Be7 13. Rb1 Rb8 14. O-O O-O 15. Re1 h6 $11) 11... Qxf6 12. O-O h6 13. Rb1 O-O-O 14. Bb5 (14. Be3 Bd6) 14... Bf5 15. Be3 a6 16. Bxc6 Qxc6 17. Nd4 Qg6 $11) (9... Nc5 $6 10. Bb5 Be7 11. Be3 O-O 12. O-O a6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qd2 $14) 10. Nxe4 (10. O-O Nc5 11. a3 Qd7 12. b4 Nxd3 13. Qxd3 Be7 14. Be3 O-O 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Rd2 f6 17. exf6 Bxf6 $11) 10... dxe4 11. Bxe4 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 13. Ke1 (13. Bd2 Bc5 $44) (13. Ke2 $144 Bc4+ 14. Ke1 Bd5) 13... Bd5 $1 $44 14. Bxd5 Rxd5 15. Bf4 Nb4 16. Rd1 Nxc2+ 17. Ke2 Nb4 18. Ng5 ({the last serious try, as the game is roughly equal after} 18. a3 Rxd1 19. Rxd1 Nc6 20. Nd4 Nxd4+ 21. Rxd4 g6 $5 22. Be3 Bg7 23. f4 f6 24. exf6 Bxf6 $11) 18... Be7 19. Nxf7 Rf8 20. e6 Rf5 21. Rd4 (21. Bg3 $6 Rf6) 21... Nc6 22. Re4 Nd8 $1 {and Black is restoring the material balance by force, as demonstrated by} 23. Rc1 Nxe6 24. Rxe6 R8xf7 25. Rxc7+ Kd8 26. Bg3 Rxf2+ 27. Kd3 (27. Bxf2 Kxc7 $11) 27... Bg5 28. Rxf7 Rxf7 $11) (4. Be3 {is inviting} Ng4 $1 {when the elimination of Be3 will be definitely an achievement:} 5. Nf3 (5. Bc4 Nxe3 6. fxe3 Qh4+ $5 7. g3 Qh6 8. Nd5 Kd8 9. Qd2 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gc7c6]}) (5. Bc1 exd4 $1 (5... Nf6) 6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qd1 (7. Bb5 Be7 8. h3 Nge5 $11) 7... f5 $1 8. h3 Nf6 9. exf5 Bxf5 10. Nf3 d5 11. Bb5 Bb4 $11) 5... Nxe3 6. fxe3 Nd7 7. Bc4 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe1 Nb6 ({other good options are} 9... c6) (9... Bf6) 10. Bb3 a5 11. a4 Be6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. b3 (13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Nxe5 Rxf1+ 15. Qxf1 Bf6 $44) 13... Qe8 $11) (4. Bc4 exd4 5. Qxd4 {We have already had a similar situation, but with h2-h3 on the board. Here Bc4 hinders the liberating d6-d5, but Black can act against it with a timely Bc8-e6, for example} Nc6 6. Qd1 (6. Qe3 g6 7. Bd2 Bg7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. Nf3 Re8 10. Rhe1 h6 $132) 6... g6 7. Nge2 Bg7 8. Bg5 (8. O-O O-O) 8... h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Be6 11. Bb3 Nh5 $11) (4. Bg5 h6 ({equally good are} 4... Nbd7) ({and} 4... Be7) 5. Be3 (5. Bh4 Nbd7 6. Nf3 c6 $11) 5... Ng4 (5... c6 6. Nf3 Nbd7 $11) 6. Bc1 exd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Qd1 Be7 $11) (4. f4 exd4 $1 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 (6. Qf2 $2 d5 $17) (6. Qe3 Be7 7. Bc4 Be6 8. Bxe6 fxe6 9. Nf3 Qd7 $11) (6. Bb5 Be7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Qd1 a6 9. Bd3 Nb4 10. Be2 c5 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 11. a3 Nc6 12. O-O b5 $11) 6... Bg4 ({it is always pleasant to develop a piece with tempo, but worth checking are also} 6... Qe7 $5 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. Nf3 O-O-O) ({and} 6... d5 $5 7. e5 d4) 7. Be2 (7. Nf3 d5 $1 8. e5 ({illogical is} 8. exd5 $6 Qe7+ 9. Qe2 Nb4 $15 {and it is unclear what the f4-pawn is doing}) 8... d4 9. exf6 dxc3 10. Qxd8+ Rxd8 11. bxc3 gxf6 $132) 7... Bxe2 8. Qxe2 Qd7 9. Bd2 O-O-O 10. O-O-O Re8 {is revealing the main drawback of the early f2-f4, for White must protect his e4-pawn only with pieces - Black has a comfortable equality after} 11. Qd3 (11. Qf3 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7]} 12. Nge2 Bg7 $11) 11... d5 12. exd5 (12. e5 $6 Ng4 $15) (12. Nxd5 Nxe4) 12... Nb4 13. Qc4 Nfxd5 (13... Nbxd5 $5 14. Nf3) 14. a3 (14. Nf3 Nb6 15. Qf1 Qf5 16. Nd4 Qf6 17. Nb3 g6 $11) 14... Nb6 15. Qb3 Nc6 $11) (4. a3 exd4 ({other normal replies are} 4... Nbd7) (4... Be7) 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd3 {Compared to the line with 4.h3, Black is lacking the motifs with Nc6-b4, but he, whilst taking care of the d5-square with a timely Bc8-e6, can switch to} g6 {and now:} 7. Bg5 (7. Bf4 Bg7 8. O-O-O Be6 $1 (8... O-O $6 9. Qd2 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf2f3]}) 9. Qd2 a6 10. Nge2 (10. Nf3 h6 11. Be2 Qe7 $11 {[%cal Ge8c8]}) 10... h6 11. f3 b5 12. Be3 Rb8 $132) 7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Bg7 10. O-O-O (10. f3 Be6) 10... Nh5 11. Nd5 (11. Nge2 Qf6 $1) 11... Ne7 12. Ne3 Be6 13. Ne2 Qd7 14. Nd4 O-O-O $11) 4... c6 {The most accurate and logical reply.} (4... Nbd7 5. g4 h6 6. h3) (4... Be7 5. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4]} c6 6. g4) 5. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4]} (5. Nf3 Be7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O a5 $11) (5. Nge2 Be7 6. h3 (6. Ng3 cxd5 7. exd5 O-O $132) 6... b5 7. a3 (7. dxc6 Nxc6 8. Ng3 a6 $11) 7... h5 $5 8. Be3 a6 $132) 5... cxd5 {The proper moment to clarify the central structure.} (5... Be7 $143 6. g4 O-O 7. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2g3]}) 6. exd5 Qa5 $1 {In combination with move 8 - an original idea to outprepare the typical f7-f5 advance and challenge by this the intended g2-g4 thrust.} 7. Nge2 (7. Bd2 Be7 8. Qf3 O-O 9. a3 (9. O-O-O Na6 $132) (9. g4 Na6 10. a3 Bd7 11. g5 Ne8 $132) 9... Na6 10. Nge2 Bd7 11. Ng3 Rfc8 12. Be2 g6 $132 13. Nce4 Qd8) (7. g4 Ne4 8. Nge2 Be7 {is just transposing.}) 7... Be7 8. g4 Ne4 $1 9. Bg2 ({The aggressive} 9. Be3 Na6 10. Qd3 f5 11. O-O-O {can be met in two different ways:} Nxc3 (11... Nac5 $5 12. Qb5+ Qxb5 13. Nxb5 f4 14. Bxc5 dxc5 {is really wild:} 15. Rh2 (15. Nc7+ Kd8 16. Nxa8 Nxf2 17. d6 Bg5 $132 {Black is holding after the critical} 18. h4 Nxh1 19. hxg5 Bxg4 20. Nc7 h5 21. gxh6 Rxh6 {, for example} 22. Bg2 ({the complications after} 22. Re1 Nf2 23. Nc3 e4 24. N7d5 g5 {seem to lead to an equal ending -} 25. Bg2 Re6 26. Nc7 Re5 27. Bxe4 Bf5 28. N7d5 Bxe4 29. Nf6 g4 30. Ncxe4 g3 31. Kd2 Nxe4+ 32. Nxe4 g2 33. Rg1 Rxe4 34. Rxg2 Kd7 35. Rg7+ Kxd6 36. Rxb7 Rb4 37. Rxa7 Rxb2 $11) ({so is with} 22. Rd5 Nf2 23. Rxe5 Rh1 24. Nxf4 Rxf1+ 25. Kd2 Rd1+ 26. Kc3 Rxd6 27. Nce6+ Ke7 28. Nxc5+ Kf6 29. Re1 b6 30. Nfd3 Nd1+ 31. Rxd1 Bxd1 32. Ne4+ Ke6 33. Nxd6 Kxd6 34. Nf2 Bf3 35. Kd4) 22... Ng3 23. Nxg3 Bxd1 24. Nf5 f3 25. Bf1 Rh1 26. Ne6+ Kc8 27. Kxd1 Rxf1+ 28. Kd2 f2 29. Ke2 Rc1 30. Kxf2 Rxc2+ 31. Kf3 g6 32. Ne3 Rxb2 33. Nc4 Rxa2 34. Ke3 Ra1 35. Kd2 Ra6 36. Nxc5 Rc6 37. d7+ Kc7 38. Nxb7 Kxd7 $11) (15. d6 Nxf2 16. dxe7 Nxd1 17. Kxd1 Kxe7 18. Nec3 Bd7 19. Nd5+ Kf7 $132) 15... f3 16. Nec3 Nxc3 17. Nxc3 Bd7 $132) 12. Nxc3 f4 13. Bd2 Bd7 $132) (9. Qd3 f5 $1 10. gxf5 Nxc3 11. Nxc3 (11. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Nxc3 Bxf5 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. cxd3 O-O $11) 11... O-O 12. Rg1 Na6 (12... Bxf5 13. Bh6 g6 {is good enough}) 13. Bh6 Rf7 14. a3 Qd8 15. Qd2 ({to say the least, Black's chances are not worse in case of} 15. O-O-O Nc5 16. Qd2 Bxf5 17. Be2 Ne4 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 $11) 15... Bxf5 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Nc5 18. Qe2 Qc8 $132) 9... Nxc3 10. Nxc3 Nd7 (10... f5 {is fully playable here as well, the game is double-edged after} 11. O-O O-O 12. f4 Nd7 $13 {, but the immediate jump is more flexible and contains another idea.}) 11. O-O (11. Be3 O-O {(if5)} 12. O-O (12. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] is White's last attempt to castle to the long -} f5 13. gxf5 Nf6 14. Qd3 Bd7 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 15. O-O-O b5 16. Kb1 Kh8 $44) 12... Nb6 13. Qd3 f5 14. a4 Bd7 15. b3 (15. gxf5 Bxf5 16. Ne4 Nd7 $11) 15... Rac8 16. Nb5 (16. Bd2 Qc5 17. a5 e4 18. Nxe4 fxe4 19. Bxe4 Bb5 20. Bxh7+ Kh8 21. c4 Nxc4 22. bxc4 Bxc4 23. Qe4 Bxf1 24. Rxf1 Qc4 25. Be3 Qxe4 26. Bxe4 Bd8 $11) 16... e4 {The position more and more resembles the trendy Sveshnikov with 7.Nd5 Nxd5 8.exd5; indeed, the g4-pawn is an attractive target.} 17. Qd1 Bf6 18. Bd2 ({Black is absolutely fine in the line} 18. Nxd6 Bxa1 19. Bxb6 Qxb6 20. Nxc8 Rxc8 21. Qxa1 Rxc2 $11) 18... Qa6 19. Rc1 (19. c4 Bxa1 20. Qxa1 {is the best version of this typical exchange sacrifice, based here on the hanging d6-pawn and the precarious location of Qa6. However, White's position is overextended and there is} Nxc4 $1 21. bxc4 Rxc4 {with rich play, e.g.} 22. Nc3 fxg4 $132) 19... Nxd5 ({anothrt option is} 19... Bxb5 20. axb5 Qxb5 21. c4 Qd7 {and Black is again a pawn up, even though for a few moves -} 22. gxf5 Qxf5 23. Qg4 Qxg4 24. hxg4 $11) 20. c4 Ne7 21. Bf4 (21. Bb4 Rcd8 22. Nc7 Qc6 23. Qxd6 fxg4 $132) 21... Rcd8 22. Nxd6 (22. gxf5 Bxf5 23. Bxd6 Bg5 $132) 22... Ng6 23. Bh2 f4 $1 {A remarkable idea to cut off Bh2, even at the cost of a pawn..} 24. Nxe4 (24. Bxe4 Bc6 25. Bd5+ Kh8 26. Ne4 Be7 $44) 24... Bc8 25. Qe2 (25. Nxf6+ Qxf6 26. Bd5+ Be6 $44) 25... Bd4 {[%csl Gd4]} 26. Ng5 ({Bd5, instead,} 26. Rcd1 Nh4 $1 {can turn Bg2 into a concern}) 26... Qf6 27. Bd5+ Kh8 28. Rcd1 Bb6 29. Nf3 Bc5 $1 {[%csl Gc5] The point of this short bishop's manoeuvre - White's queemside majority is practically nullified.} 30. Be4 Rde8 31. Rd5 b6 32. Rh5 Bb7 33. Ng5 h6 34. Qc2 Bxe4 35. Nxe4 Qc6 36. Nxc5 bxc5 $44) 11... Nf8 $5 {[%cal Gf8g6] Here it is - Black is fighting against the analogous advance of the f2-pawn.} 12. f4 {White has hardly anything better at his disposal, for instance} ({Now and then} 12. Ne4 Ng6 13. c4 f5 $1 14. gxf5 Bxf5 {has to be checked:} 15. c5 (15. Be3 O-O 16. c5 Qd8 $132 (16... Nh4 $5 17. cxd6 Bd8)) 15... Bxe4 16. Bxe4 Qxc5 17. Be3 Qc4 18. Qf3 (18. Qg4 Nf4) 18... Rf8 19. Qg2 Nf4 20. Bxf4 Rxf4 21. Bxh7 Rc8 22. Qxg7 Kd8 $11) 12... Qb6+ $1 13. Kh1 ({Looks a bit safer than} 13. Kh2 exf4 14. Bxf4 Ng6 15. Bg3 O-O $132 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ge7h4]}) 13... exf4 14. Bxf4 Ng6 15. Bg3 (15. Bh2 O-O {seems similar, but it makes more sense to keep an eye at h4.}) 15... O-O 16. Qd3 {Once again White has to reckon with the common push f7-f5,} ({as witnessed by} 16. Ne4 f5 $1 17. gxf5 Bxf5 18. Qe2 Rae8 19. Rxf5 Rxf5 20. Nxd6 Re5 $1 21. Ne4 $1 Qxb2 22. Rf1 Bd6 23. Qd3 Rxe4 24. Bxe4 Bxg3 25. Qxg3 Qd4 26. Bg2 Rf8 $11) ({and} 16. a4 f5 $1 17. gxf5 Rxf5 18. Ne4 Bd7 19. a5 Qc7 $11) 16... Bd7 (16... Qxb2 17. Ne4 Qb6 18. g5 $36) 17. a4 Rac8 18. Ra3 {An indirect protection of the hanging b2-pawn, though this rook will be temporarily misplaced there, especially after Black's reply.} (18. Ne4 f5 $1 $132 19. gxf5 $140 Rxf5 20. c4 (20. Rxf5 {assures White of the pair of bishops after} Bxf5 21. Nf6+ Bxf6 22. Qxf5 Re8 {, but, due to the full control over the e5-square, Black has little to complain about, for example} 23. Qd7 Rd8 24. Qe6+ Kh8 25. Rf1 Be5 $11) 20... Rcf8 21. a5 Rxf1+ 22. Rxf1 Qxa5 23. Nxd6 Qb4 $11) 18... Qd8 {Disabling Ra3-b3, so} 19. a5 ({In the new situation} 19. Ne4 f5 $1 20. Nxd6 {will be countered with} f4 21. Nxc8 Bxa3 22. Qxa3 Qxc8 23. Be1 Qxc2 $132) 19... Nh4 $1 20. Be4 g6 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 21. Raa1 a6 {[%cal Gf7f5]} ({Worth checking is} 21... f5 22. Bxh4 fxe4 23. Bxe7 Qxe7 24. Qxe4 Qg5 $44) 22. Qe2 Bg5 23. Bd3 Re8 24. Qh2 (24. Qf2 f5 $132) 24... f5 $132 *

