1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nge2 {This is by fat not an innocuous move! In fact, White is declaring his intentions not just to bring a bishop to g2, but to realize that after gainig space with h2-h3, followed by g2-g4, thus winning an essential tempo in comparison to the usual (with g2-g3) systems with fianchettoed bishop.} c6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ({Now and then the natural developing move} 4... Be7 {can suit better White.}) 5. h3 {Besides this program move, White can also choose from:} (5. a4 {is an ambitious try to stiffle Black's counterplay. Indeed, such strategy looks too wide, but it is not easy to find an antidote. Continuing the development with} Be7 {in connection with a timely opening the center by ....exd4 seems to be the most principled way to proceed:} 6. g3 (6. h3 O-O 7. g4 (7. Be3 Na6 $132) 7... exd4 $1 8. Qxd4 (8. Nxd4 $6 d5 $15) 8... d5 {and Ke1 is a concern, for instance} 9. exd5 cxd5 10. Be3 Nc6 11. Qd2 Be6 $132) {tends to spare a tempo for castling, but Black's plan for} 6... exd4 $1 7. Nxd4 (7. Qxd4 d5 $1 8. exd5 cxd5 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 9. Bg2 Nc6 10. Qd1 d4 11. Nb5 Bc5 $11) 7... O-O 8. Bg2 d5 $1 {remains the same -} 9. e5 ({the transformation of the central configuration with} 9. exd5 cxd5 {will once again make 5.a4 looking useless, e.g.} 10. O-O Nc6 11. h3 h6 12. Be3 Re8 $11) 9... Ng4 10. f4 f6 11. e6 f5 12. h3 Nf6 13. g4 (13. Nxf5 Bc5) 13... Ne4 $132) (5. g3 b5 $1 6. a3 Nbd7 7. Bg2 Be7 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8b7]}) (5. Be3 {allows} b5 {as well, Black is fine, as shown by} 6. a3 Nbd7 7. Ng3 (7. d5 Bb7 8. dxc6 Bxc6 9. Ng3 a6 10. Be2 g6 $11 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gh7h5]}) 7... h5 $1 8. Bg5 (8. h4 Ng4) 8... a6 9. Be2 g6 $132) 5... b5 $1 {There is no particular reason to wait with this thematic advance.} (5... Be7 $143 6. g4 O-O 7. Bg2 $36) 6. a3 ({White does not have time for 6.g4, but deviating from the general plan with} 6. Ng3 {may encourage his opponent to expand on by} h5 $1 7. Bg5 h4 8. Nf5 b4 {and now:} 9. Nb1 (9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Na4 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Nbd7 12. f3 Nb6 13. Nxb6 axb6 14. Nd6+ (14. Bxh4 Be6 $44) 14... Bxd6 15. Rxd6 Rxa2 16. Rxc6 O-O 17. b3 Be6 18. Bxh4 Rfa8 $44) 9... Bxf5 10. exf5 exd4 11. Qxd4 d5 12. Bd3 Nbd7 13. O-O Bd6 14. Nd2 (14. Re1+ Kf8) 14... Qc7 15. Nf3 c5 16. Qe3+ Kf8 17. c4 bxc3 18. bxc3 Re8 19. Qd2 Ne4 20. Bxe4 dxe4 21. Rfd1 (21. Nxh4 Nf6 $44 {[%csl Rh4]}) 21... exf3 22. Qxd6+ Qxd6 23. Rxd6 Nb6 24. Rc6 (24. f6 Rh5 25. fxg7+ Kxg7 26. Bf6+ Kh7 $11) 24... Rh5 25. Be3 Rxf5 26. Rxc5 Rxc5 27. Bxc5+ Kg8 28. gxf3 Rc8 29. Bd4 Rc7 30. Kf1 f6 31. Ke2 (31. Rb1 Nd5) 31... Nd5 $11 {[%csl Rf3,Rh3][%cal Gd5c3,Gd5f4]}) 6... h5 $1 {A reciprocal to 5.a4 restrictive strategy.} (6... Be7 $143 7. g4 $36) 7. Ng1 $5 {A fresh idea, which is often seen in some Sicilian branches as well - this knight will be rerouted to the g5-square. Here are the alternatives in brief:} (7. f4 Nbd7 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. fxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {leads to an endgame with mutual chances -} 11. Bf4 Nfd7 (11... Bd6 12. O-O-O Kc7 13. Bh2 {is also unclear}) 12. O-O-O (12. Nd4 Bb7 13. O-O-O Kc7 14. Be2 (14. a4 a6) 14... Re8 15. a4 (15. Rhf1 f6) 15... a6 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rhf1 f6 $11) 12... f6 13. Nd4 Ke7 {[%cal Ge7f7]} 14. Be2 (14. Nf5+ Kf7 15. Nd6+ Ke6 16. Nxc8 Rxc8 $11) 14... g6 15. g4 hxg4 16. hxg4 Rxh1 17. Rxh1 Kf7 18. g5 Bg7 $11 {, as in Iglesias Ferreira - Matamoros Franco, Linares, 2024, looks pretty solid for Black, who has successfully coped with the opponent's temporary initiative.}) (7. Be3 {is very natural.} Nbd7 8. Ng1 $5 (8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Ng1 Bc5 10. Qd2 O-O 11. Nf3 Re8 $11) (8. g3 Bb7 9. Bg2 Be7 {is balanced}) 8... exd4 $5 ({preparing to ask questions to the e4-pawn; Black can also continue with the restrained} 8... Be7 9. Nf3 a6 10. Be2 Bb7 $132) 9. Qxd4 (9. Bxd4 a6 10. Nf3 Bb7 $132 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gc6c5]}) 9... Bb7 10. Nf3 Be7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O a5 $132) ({as mentioned,} 7. g3 Nbd7 8. Bg2 Be7 9. Be3 Bb7 $132 {is satisfactory for Black}) (7. Bg5 Be7 8. Ng3 g6 $132) (7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. f4 {is quite similar to 7.f4 from above and may transpose to it, her Black has the alternative} Bd6 10. Be3 Kc7 {and now:} 11. O-O-O (11. fxe5 Bxe5 12. O-O-O Re8 13. Nd4 a6 14. Bd3 (14. Be2 Nbd7 15. Rhf1 Bb7 $11) 14... c5 15. Nf3 Bxc3 16. Bf4+ Kb7 17. bxc3 c4 18. e5 cxd3 19. exf6 gxf6 20. Rxd3 Nc6 $11) 11... exf4 12. Nxf4 a6 13. Be2 Nbd7 14. Rxd6 (14. Rhf1 Bb7 $11) 14... Kxd6 15. Rd1+ (15. Nd3 $5 {is venomous either, White has compensation for the exchange, but hardly more after} Ne5 16. Bc5+ Ke6 17. Nf4+ Kd7 18. Rd1+ Ke8 19. Bd6 Nfd7 20. Nxh5 Rh7 $1) 15... Kc7 16. Nd3 Bb7 $1 17. Bf4+ Kb6 18. Bf3 (18. Be3+ $6 c5) (18. b4 Rae8) 18... Rae8 19. b4 Ka7 $132) (7. d5 a6 {is safe enough -} 8. Be3 Be7 (8... Bb7) 9. g3 Bb7 10. dxc6 Bxc6 {[%cal Gb8d7]} 11. Bg2 Nbd7 $132) 7... Be7 ({Black can start with} 7... Nbd7 {as well.}) 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. Be2 (9. Be3 {- see 7.Be3 Nbd7 8.Ng1 Be7 9.Nf3 from above.}) 9... Bb7 10. O-O ({The move order} 10. Ng5 a6 11. f4 Qc7 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. O-O {is surrounding the small tactical opportunity in the text, but Black is the first to step on the open d-file and look for his chances after} Rd8 14. Qe1 c5 15. Bf3 c4 16. Kh1 Nc5 $132) 10... a6 11. Ng5 Qc7 12. f4 {A bold advance without a preliminary Bc1-e3.} (12. Re1 Rd8 $132) 12... exd4 $1 13. Qxd4 d5 $1 {Of course!} 14. Qf2 {This retreat is almost a must.} (14. Kh1 $2 c5 $17) 14... Bc5 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 dxe4 17. Ncxe4 (17. Ngxe4 O-O $11) (17. Rad1 O-O $11) 17... O-O 18. Ng3 (18. Rad1 Rae8 $11) 18... Rae8 19. Qf2 g6 20. f5 ({To} 20. Rae1 {, which overprotects Be2, pretty solid is} h4 21. Nh1 Qb6 $11) 20... h4 21. Nh1 Re5 22. Bg4 (22. Rae1 Rxf5 23. Qxh4 {looks dangerous, but, as the h7-square is defended, Black can confidently continue with} Qb6+ 24. Nf2 ({Black's prospects are not worse after} 24. Kh2 Rxf1 25. Rxf1 Kg7 26. Ng3 c5) 24... Kg7 25. Bd3 Rh8 {and} 26. Qg3 {will logically result in a draw by repetion -} Nh5 27. Qh4 Nf4 28. Qg3 Nh5 $11) 22... Qb6 {The simplest - without the queens all White's hopes to launch an attack are evaporating.} 23. Qxb6 Nxb6 24. fxg6 (24. Nf3 Nxg4 25. hxg4 Re2 26. fxg6 fxg6 27. Nxh4 Rxf1+ 28. Rxf1 Nd5 $44 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gd5e3]}) 24... Rxg5 25. Rxf6 Rxg6 26. Rxg6+ fxg6 $11 *

