1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 {The most logical continuation, here are other possible options in brief:} ({The insertion of} 6. a3 Bd6 {[%cal Gd8e7]} {before} 7. Bc4 (7. Nf3 c6 {[%cal Gd8e7]}) {allows Black to regroup -} 7... Ke7 8. Bg5 (8. f3 Be6 $11) 8... c6 9. O-O-O Bc7 10. Nge2 h6 11. Bh4 Nbd7 $11) (6. Bd3 {is too modest -} Bd6 7. Nf3 c6 8. Nd2 Be6 9. Nc4 Bc7 10. a4 a5 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7]}) (6. Be3 {can be met by} Bb4 7. O-O-O+ Nbd7 8. f3 Bxc3 9. bxc3 Ke7 $11) (6. Bd2 {[%cal Ge1c1]} Bd6 {is also fine for Black, who has secured the comfortable e7-square for his king, after} 7. O-O-O {he has the luxury to choose where to place his light-squared bishop, for instance, it is possible to fianchettoe it after} Nbd7 8. f3 (8. Bc4 Ke7) 8... c6 {b5}) (6. f3 Be6 (6... c6 $144) 7. f4 $6 ({a bizarre idea, after which Black has every reason to look for more than equality; the play is equal in case of normal developing moves like} 7. Be3 Nbd7) ({or} 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. O-O-O c6 $11) 7... Bb4 $1 8. Bd3 exf4 9. Bxf4 Nbd7 $11 {/?}) (6. f4 Nbd7 (6... Bb4 {is a plausible alternative, when possible}) 7. Nf3 Bd6 $11) (6. Nf3 {should be answered with} Bd6 $1 {and now:} 7. Be3 (7. Bc4 Ke7 8. Bg5 {will be met by the cool-blooded} Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6]} 9. Nd5+ $140 (9. O-O-O Nb6 $1) 9... Ke8 10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. Nxf6+ gxf6 12. Rd1 a5 $11) (7. Bg5 {at once is providing Black with} Be6 $1) 7... Ke7 8. h3 (8. Nd2 Be6 9. f3 Nbd7 10. Nc4 Bb4 11. Bd2 a5 $11) 8... Be6 9. Ng5 Nbd7 10. Nxe6 Kxe6 11. Bc4+ Ke7 {[%cal Gd6c5]} 12. O-O-O Bc5 $11) (6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. O-O-O (7. Bc4 Ke8 {may also transpose to 7.Bg5, see below}) 7... c6 8. Bc4 (8. Nf3 Kc7) 8... Ke8 9. a4 (9. Nf3 b5) 9... Bc5 10. f3 {and here the instructive} Nf8 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gf8e6] will be examined later as well.}) 6... Ke8 (6... Be6 {is the other main line -} 7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. f3 $14) 7. Nf3 (7. Bd2 {, which does not seem to pretend for much, heads to a simple development, Black has a pleasant choice -} Bd6 ({worthy alternatives are} 7... Nbd7 {and}) (7... Nc6) 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. Nf3 (9. Bg5 Be6 10. Bxe6 fxe6 $11) 9... a6 {and now:} 10. Bg5 (10. Ng5 {is neutralized by} Nd8) (10. Rhe1 Bg4 11. Nd5 (11. Bg5 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nd4 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Nd5 c6 15. Nxf6+ Ke7 16. c3 Kxf6 {and here} 17. f4 $5 {is a brilliant intermezzo, but Black can keep the balance by} Nb5 $1 18. Bxb5 Rad8 $1 19. Bf1 Ke7 $11 {and White's extra pawn is not felt at all, a draw looks inevitable}) 11... Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Nd8 13. h3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Ke7 {The push} 15. f4 {is once again worth a try, but Black has} exf4 16. e5 Bc5 17. Bxf4 Ne6 {with a pretty solid position, for instance} 18. Bg3 c6 19. Bh4+ (19. Bc4 h5) 19... g5 20. Bxe6 gxh4 21. Bg4 Rad8 $11) 10... Be6 11. Bd5 (11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Ne1 h6 13. Bd2 b5 14. f3 Nd7 $11) 11... Bxd5 12. exd5 Ne7 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. g4 h5 15. Ne4 Rh6 16. h3 Kd7 {and Black is ready to double his rooks, while Bd6 is cementing the center -} 17. c4 b6 $11) ({In reply to} 7. f4 {the sally} Bb4 $1 {seems to be the critical reaction:} 8. Bd3 (8. Bd2 exf4 (8... Be6 {is also perfectly playable}) 9. Nge2 Nc6 $11) ({the game can sharpen to utmost after the uncompromising} 8. Nf3 Nxe4 9. Nxe5 Nxc3 10. a3 {- Black can sacrifice the f7-pawn for speedy mobilization, e.g.} Bc5 11. bxc3 Ke7 12. Nxf7 Re8 13. Kd2 (13. Ne5 Nd7) 13... Kf6 14. Re1 (14. Ne5 Nc6 $44) 14... Rxe1 15. Kxe1 Nc6 16. Ng5 Bf5 $44 17. Bd3 $140 h6 18. Nf3 Re8+ 19. Kf1 Rd8 20. Ke2 Re8+ $11) 8... Nbd7 9. Nf3 {is also exerting maximum pressure on the e5-pawn, Black seems to hold with the help of a timely counterattack -} Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nc5 11. O-O (11. fxe5 Nfxe4 $11) 11... Nfxe4 12. Re1 Nxd3 13. cxd3 Nd6 14. c4 (14. fxe5 Nf5) 14... Be6 {and White will regain the pawn, but Ke8 is by no means obliged to castle, as witnessed by:} 15. Bb2 (15. Rxe5 Kd7 16. Nd4 g6 17. Nxe6 (17. Bb2 Rhe8) 17... fxe6 18. Re2 Rhf8 $11) 15... exf4 16. Bxg7 Rg8 17. Be5 (17. Bh6 Rd8 18. Bxf4 Kd7 19. Ng5 Rg7 $11) 17... Kd7 18. Bxf4 Rae8 $11) (7. Bg5 Nbd7 8. Nf3 ({as you already know, after} 8. O-O-O c6 9. a4 {Black has the instructive} Bc5 10. f3 Nf8 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6]} {with promising play on the dark squares after} 11. Nge2 Be6 12. Bxe6 Nxe6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 $11) {and Black can make use of the move order by the more active} 8... Bb4 9. Bd2 (9. O-O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 h6 11. Bh4 Ke7 12. Bg3 (12. Rhe1 Re8 $11 {[%cal Ge7f8]}) 12... Nxe4 13. Bxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Nd6 15. Bb3 Re8 $11) 9... c6 10. a3 (10. O-O-O b5 11. Bd3 Bc5 12. Rhf1 Ke7 $132) 10... Bd6 (10... Bc5 $144) 11. a4 Ke7 12. O-O-O Nb6 13. Bb3 Be6 $11) (7. Nge2 c6 8. a4 a5 9. Be3 Na6 $11) ({As on the previous move,} 7. Be3 {allows} Bb4 {in one go -} 8. f3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nc6 $11) (7. a3 $5 {can be similarly answered with} a6 ({possible are both} 7... c6) ({and} 7... Bd6) 8. Nf3 (8. Bg5 b5 {(there is no particular reason to postpone this thematic advance)} 9. Ba2 Nbd7 10. O-O-O h6 11. Bxf6 (11. Bh4 Rb8 12. Nge2 Be7 $11) (11. Bd2 c6 12. f4 a5 13. Nf3 b4 $132) 11... Nxf6 12. Nd5 Bd6 13. Nxf6+ gxf6 $11) (8. f4 Nc6 9. Nd5 ({too optimistic, Black has enough resources to meet} 9. Nf3 {either -} Bd6 10. Ng5 Rf8 $132) 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Nd4 11. Bd3 Bd6 12. fxe5 Bxe5 $11) 8... Bd6 9. Be3 (9. Bg5 b5 10. Ba2 Nbd7 11. O-O-O h6 12. Bd2 Bb7 13. Rhe1 Kf8 $11 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7]}) 9... Nc6 10. h3 h6 {transposes to the main line.}) 7... Bd6 8. h3 Nc6 (8... a6 {is very similar to the text.}) 9. a3 (9. Be3 {looks consistent, in reply to it a fighting option is} Bb4 $5 ({solid is the common} 9... a6 10. a4 h6 11. Nd2 Ke7 {[%cal Gc8e6]} 12. f3 Be6 $11) 10. Nd2 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Ke7 {[%cal Gc8e6]} (11... Be6 $6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. f3 $14) 12. Bc5+ (12. O-O-O Rd8 {[%cal Gc8e6]} 13. f4 Be6 $11) 12... Ke8 13. O-O-O Be6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. f3 Nd7 16. Nb3 Nb6 17. Rd3 Rd8 18. Rhd1 {and time has come for Black to reming the opponent of the vulnerability of his queenside pawns -} Na4 $11) 9... h6 10. Be3 a6 {Both sides have accurately made all the small prophylactic moves, the position remains equal.} 11. Ba2 (11. O-O Be6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Rfd1 Ke7 $11 {[%cal Gg7g5]}) (11. O-O-O b5 12. Ba2 Be6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Nd2 Ke7 15. Nb3 Nd7 $11) 11... Be6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Nd2 Ke7 14. Nb3 Rhd8 15. O-O-O ({Less precise is} 15. Ke2 {in the view of} a5 $1 16. a4 Bb4 $132) 15... b5 $5 {The doubled e-pawns, which are keeping important central squares under control, seem in safety, so it is natural for Black to expand on the queenside.} (15... Nd7 $143 16. Na4 $1) 16. Nc5 (16. f3 Nd7 $11) 16... Na5 17. f3 Nd7 18. Nxd7 Rxd7 $11 *

