1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Be2 (5. a4 Be7 {is about to transpose on the next moves.}) (5. Bd3 {deserves to be studied, for in the main lines with 5.Bc4 this bishop is often moving to d3 afterwards.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 (7... Re8 $144) 8. a4 Re8 9. h3 exd4 (9... h6 {is also possible}) 10. Nxd4 Nc5 11. Bf4 Bf8 12. Qf3 (12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Bd7 (13... a5 {is yet another good option}) 14. Qf3 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 (15. cxd3 Be7 $14) 15... g5 $5 (15... Be7 {[%cal Gd8c7]}) 16. Bg3 Nh5 17. Bh2 Qf6 18. Nde2 Rad8 $132) 12... Nxd3 13. Qxd3 (13. cxd3 a5 $11) 13... h6 14. Rad1 Bd7 15. Nf3 d5 16. exd5 (16. e5 Nh7 17. Ne2 Qc8 {[%cal Gd7f5]} 18. c4 Bf5 19. Qc3 a5 $11) 16... Nxd5 17. Rxe8 (17. Nxd5 cxd5 18. Rxe8 Bxe8 19. b3 Qf6 20. Be3 Bc6 $11) 17... Bxe8 18. b3 a6 $5 ({a pawn sacrifice, Black is going to put his hopes on the powerful bishops. However, if he is not in a sacrificial mood, then} 18... Rc8 {is a reasonable continuation}) 19. Nxd5 cxd5 20. Qxd5 Qxd5 21. Rxd5 b5 22. axb5 (22. a5 Rc8 23. Nd4 f6 $44) 22... axb5 23. Ne1 (23. Nd4 f6 $44) 23... f6 $44) (5. g3 {is not ideallly correlating to Ng1-f3, as the knight is staying on the way of the f2-pawn, so Black will keep the center closed -} c6 {[%cal Gb7b5] and now:} 6. a4 (6. Bg2 Be7 (6... b5 {is more or less normal, but after} 7. O-O {Black should reckon with} Be7 8. Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4f5]}) 7. O-O O-O 8. a4 {transposes to the next line}) 6... Be7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O b6 ({one of the standard replies to the march of the rook's pawn, but Black can also ignore it by} 8... Re8) ({or} 8... Qc7) 9. Be3 ({or} 9. Re1 a6 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ga8b8,Gb6b5,Gc8b7,Gf8e8] , building a hedgehog-like structure with a preparation for b6-b5 on the next moves}) 9... a6 ({worth checking is} 9... Bb7 $5 10. a5 $140 b5 11. a6 Bc8 $13) 10. h3 (10. Nh4 {is the move, which can justify White's choices on moves 4 and 5. Wven after a weakening like} g6 {Black seems to be solid enough, for example} 11. f4 Bb7 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. a5 (13. f5 b5 14. Qf3 Bc5 $132) 13... b5 14. Qe2 Bc5 15. f5 Qe7 $132) (10. Nd2 {must be also connected with a standard queenside expansion, but White can also meet} Bb7 {with} 11. d5 ({a position with mutual chances is arising after} 11. g4 h6 12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 b5 $132) 11... cxd5 12. exd5 b5 13. axb5 axb5 14. b4 {is a very ambitious plan to fix and win the b5-pawn, but Black can initiate counterplay on the kingside by means of} Rxa1 15. Qxa1 Nb6 $1 16. Qa2 (16. Qa7 Nbxd5) 16... Ng4 $1 17. Qa7 Nxe3 18. fxe3 Bg5 $1 19. Qxb7 (19. Re1 Ba8 $132) 19... Bxe3+ 20. Rf2 f5 $1 {[%cal Gf5f4]} 21. Nf1 (21. Nxb5 f4 22. Ne4 fxg3 23. hxg3 Rxf2 24. Nxf2 Qf8 $11) 21... Qb8 22. Qxb8 Bxf2+ 23. Kxf2 Rxb8 $132) 10... Re8 11. g4 (11. Qe2 Bf8 12. d5 cxd5 13. exd5 g6 $132) ({here} 11. Nh4 g6 12. f4 {can be met by} exf4 13. Bxf4 Bb7 14. Bh6 (14. Qf3 c5 15. d5 Ne5 16. Bxe5 dxe5 $132) 14... b5 15. Qd2 b4 16. Nd1 c5 $5 17. e5 Bxg2 18. exf6 Bxf1 19. fxe7 Qxe7 20. Kxf1 Qf6+ 21. Nf2 cxd4 22. Bf4 Qe6 $1 23. Qxd4 Rac8 $132) 11... h6 $1 12. g5 ({in case of} 12. Nd2 Bb7 13. f4 {Black can disable the next step of the g-pawn by} Nh7 $1 14. Qf3 $140 exd4 15. Bxd4 b5 $132) 12... hxg5 13. Nxg5 Nf8 14. f4 {is yet another kingside assault, but Black is holding in the forced line} exf4 15. Rxf4 (15. Bxf4 Ne6 16. Nxe6 Bxe6 $11) 15... N8h7 16. Rh4 Ng4 $1 17. Nxf7 Nxe3 18. Qh5 Qd7 19. Qxh7+ Kxf7 20. Rh6 (20. Qh5+ Kg8 $11) 20... Rf8 $1 21. Qg6+ Kg8 $11) (5. d5 {is naturally answered with} c6 6. Be2 ({White will have to take on d5 with a pawn even after} 6. Nd2 Nb6 7. Nc4 Nxc4 8. Bxc4 b5 9. Bb3 b4 10. Ne2 cxd5 11. exd5 {, Black, in his turn, has seized space on the queenside and has decent chances in the ensuing middlegame with a structure, which is much more typical for the Sicilian Najdorf -} a5 12. a3 Rb8 13. O-O Be7 $132) ({similar is} 6. a4 cxd5 7. exd5 Be7) 6... cxd5 7. exd5 Be7 8. a4 Qa5 9. O-O O-O $11) (5. Be3 $5 Be7 (5... c6 6. h3 {is probably of no independent significance}) 6. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4]} c6 7. g4 (7. a4 O-O {and Black can ask questions to the "centralized" Ke1:} 8. Bd3 (8. g4 d5 $1 9. exd5 Qa5 10. dxc6 bxc6 $132) (8. Be2 d5 9. Nxe5 (9. exd5 e4) 9... Nxe4 $11) (8. a5 exd4 9. Qxd4 b5 10. axb6 Nxb6 $11) 8... exd4 ({at once or after the preparatory} 8... Re8 9. O-O Bf8) 9. Bxd4 (9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. O-O d5 $11) 9... Qc7 10. O-O Ne5 11. Re1 b6 12. Bf1 Re8 $11) (7. Qd2 $6 b5 8. a3 Bb7 $15) 7... h6 {transposes to the next Chapter.}) 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 b6 $5 (7... c6 {is quite common even after 7.Bc4, here} 8. a5 {can inspire Black to strike at the enemy center by} exd4 $1 9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. Bf3 (10. f3 d5 $1 11. e5 Ne8 12. a6 f6 $1 13. axb7 Bxb7 $132) 10... Re8 11. Re1 Bf8 $13) 8. Re1 (8. d5 Nc5 9. Nd2 a5 10. Bb5 {is designed to occupy the exposed light squares, but, as it is not easy to open filles on the queenside, Black can rely on a timely f7-f5 after} Nfd7 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ge7g5]} 11. Bc6 Rb8 12. Nc4 Ba6 13. Qe2 Bg5 $138) (8. a5 bxa5 9. Be3 ({of course not} 9. Rxa5 $2 c5 $17) (9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Rxa5 c6 11. Ra1 Qc7 {[%cal Ga7a5]} 12. Be3 a5 $11) 9... c6 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nd2 Qc7 12. Nb3 Bb4 $11) (8. Bc4 Bb7 9. d5 (9. Re1 {is just transposing}) 9... c6 $132) 8... Bb7 9. Bc4 a6 ({Black can prefer} 9... c6 {and prove that Bf1-e2-c4 has dropped a valuable tempo.}) (9... h6 $5) 10. d5 (10. h3 c6 $11 {[%cal Gb6b5]}) 10... a5 11. b3 (11. Nd2 Nc5) 11... Nc5 12. Nd2 Kh8 13. Ba3 g6 ({As said, Black will go for f7-f5, which can be prepared by} 13... Ng8 $5 {as well.}) 14. b4 axb4 15. Bxb4 Nfd7 16. Nb3 f5 17. a5 Nxb3 18. cxb3 bxa5 19. Bxa5 Nf6 $11 *

