1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. h3 $5 Be7 (5... c6 {will probably transpose in few moves.}) 6. g4 h6 $1 ({Here Black should better refrain from} 6... c6 7. g5 Nh5 8. a4 O-O 9. Be3 $36) 7. Be3 (7. Qe2 {is overprotecting the e4-pawn with ideas to castle to the long.} c6 8. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} Qc7 9. Bb2 b5 10. O-O-O a5 11. Qe3 (11. Rg1 $144 a4 12. Qe3) 11... a4 12. Rg1 axb3 13. axb3 Nf8 14. Ne2 Ne6 $1 15. Ng3 ({Black has an ample compensation due to the open a-file after} 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Bxe5 Ba3+ 17. Kb1 Qa5 $132) (15. h4 d5 $1 {should be met by} 16. Nxe5 Nxe4 17. Bg2 Nd6 {and it is already White, who can sacrifice a pawn for an initiative by} 18. f4 Bxh4 19. Rh1 Be7 20. Kb1 Ra6 $132) 15... d5 $1 16. Nf5 (16. dxe5 Bc5 $132) 16... Ba3 $1 17. Bd3 (17. Nxe5 O-O $132) 17... c5 $1 {A stunning blow!} 18. Bxb5+ (18. dxe5 d4 19. Bxb5+ Kf8 {is simply transposing}) 18... Kf8 19. dxe5 (19. Nxe5 Bxb2+ 20. Kxb2 cxd4 21. Qg3 Nf4 $1 {will force White to find several only moves for staying in the game -} 22. Ra1 $1 Rxa1 23. Rxa1 Qxe5 24. Ra8 Kg8 $1 25. Rxc8+ Kh7 26. Rxh8+ Kxh8 27. c3 $3 Nxe4 28. cxd4 Qb8 29. Qe3 Qxb5 30. Qxf4 Qe2+ 31. Ka3 Qa6+ $11) 19... d4 20. Qe1 Bb4 (20... Nxe4 $5 21. Qxe4 Bb7 22. Qd3 Qa5 23. Ba4 Bxb2+ 24. Kxb2 Nf4 25. Qd2 Bxf3 26. Qxa5 Rxa5 27. Ra1 g6 $132) 21. Qxb4 $5 ({a great effort to take over the initiative rather than} 21. c3 dxc3 22. Bxc3 Bxc3 23. Qxc3 Nxe4 24. Qe1 Bb7 $44) 21... cxb4 22. exf6 gxf6 23. N3xd4 Nxd4 24. Nxd4 {White seems to have enough compensation for the queen, here the most practical idea is to eliminate Bb2 by} Ra2 $5 {[%cal Ga2b2]} 25. Kb1 $140 Rxb2+ 26. Kxb2 {with approximate equality after} Kg7 27. f3 Rd8 $11) (7. g5 hxg5 8. Nxg5 Nh7 $5 9. Nf3 Ng5 $132) (7. Bc4 c6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 8. a4 O-O $132) (7. Rg1 c6 8. a4 ({for} 8. Be3 {see 8.Rg1 below}) 8... exd4 $1 $146 {looks like a sound improvement:} 9. Qxd4 {is instructively countered with} (9. Nxd4 Nc5 (9... d5 $5) 10. Qf3 Qb6 $1 11. Qe3 a5 ({here} 11... d5 {is even more appropriate, e.g.} 12. a5 Qb4 13. Bd2 Ne6 $13) 12. b3 Bd7 13. Bb2 O-O-O 14. O-O-O Rhe8 15. Kb1 Bf8 16. Bg2 Nfxe4 17. Bxe4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 d5 19. f3 f6 $11) 9... Ne5 $1 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Qxe5 Be6 {with plenty of compensation for the pawn, as White can hardly find a safe shelter for his king.} 12. a5 (12. Be2 Nd7 13. Qg3 Qa5 14. Bd2 Bb4 $44) 12... Nd7 (12... Bd6 13. Qd4 Qc7 $44) 13. Qh2 (13. Qg3 Bh4) 13... b5 14. Be3 O-O $44) (7. dxe5 Nxe5 $1 ({a necessary precaution - imprecise is} 7... dxe5 8. Bc4 $36) 8. Be3 c6 9. Nd4 Qa5 $5 10. Nb3 ({worth checking is} 10. Bg2 g5 $1 11. Qe2 Be6 $132) 10... Qc7 11. f4 Ng6 12. Nd4 (12. Qf3 b5 $132) (12. a4 d5 $1 13. e5 (13. f5 Nh4 14. Qe2 O-O 15. O-O-O Re8 16. exd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 cxd5 18. Qf2 Bd7 19. Bf4 Qb6 $132) 13... Ne4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 {looks critical:} 15. Bc4 (15. Bg2 {is ambitiously looking at the e4-pawn, after} Bh4+ 16. Kd2 O-O 17. Qf1 f5 $1 {is likely to offer enough counterplay -} 18. Qc4+ Kh8 19. Raf1 Bg3 20. Kc1 fxg4 21. Qb4 (21. Qxe4 Bf5 22. Qc4 $140 Qf7 $1) 21... a5 22. Qd2 Be6 23. Bxe4 Rad8 24. Qxa5 Qxa5 25. Nxa5 Bxf4 26. Bxf4 Nxf4 27. Nxb7 Rd4 28. Nc5 gxh3 29. Rxf4 Rxf4 30. Nxe6 Rdxe4 31. Nxf4 Rxa4 32. Rxh3 Rxf4 33. Kd2 Kg8 34. Rc3 Re4 35. Rxc6 Rxe5 36. b4 h5 37. c4 {and the mutual race seems to finish without a winner, for instance} h4 38. b5 h3 39. b6 h2 40. b7 h1=Q 41. b8=Q+ Kh7 42. Qxe5 Qxc6 $11) 15... O-O 16. O-O b5 $1 17. Be2 ({a neat tactical justification is given by} 17. axb5 $6 cxb5 18. Bxb5 Nxe5 $1 $15) 17... Rd8 18. Qe1 a5 19. Nd2 (19. Qg3 Rb8 $132) 19... Rb8 20. Nxe4 bxa4 21. Bd3 Rxb2 22. Rxa4 Rb4 23. Rxb4 axb4 $132) 12... O-O 13. Qf3 b5 14. g5 ({more or less provoked, as} 14. a3 c5 15. Ndxb5 Qc6 {sets the e4-pawn on fire}) 14... hxg5 15. fxg5 Nd7 16. O-O-O Nde5 {and the possession over the e5-square should serve well to Black, for example:} 17. Qg3 (17. Qg2 b4 18. Na4 f5 $1 19. Nxf5 (19. exf5 Nh4) 19... Bxf5 20. exf5 Rxf5 21. h4 Raf8 $132) 17... d5 $1 18. Kb1 b4 19. Nce2 c5 20. Nf5 dxe4 21. Nxe7+ Nxe7 22. Bf4 N7g6 23. Bc1 Bf5 24. h4 Rad8 25. Bh3 (25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. h5 Ne7 $132) 25... Rxd1 26. Rxd1 Bxh3 27. Qxh3 Rd8 28. Rxd8+ Qxd8 29. h5 Ne7 $11) 7... c6 8. a4 {An ambitious approach to stop the counterplay with b7-b5 and keep his own ongoing kingside expansion. Such White's strategy with active pawn advances on both flanks is too broad, but its drawbacks can be revealed only by very sharp and resolute measures.} ({Both} 8. Qd2 b5 9. Bd3 Bb7 $132) ({and} 8. Rg1 b5 {are leading to positions with mutual chances, for example:} 9. g5 (9. a3 Qc7 10. g5 (10. h4 Nf8 11. g5 hxg5 12. hxg5 Ng4 $132) 10... hxg5 11. Nxg5 Rb8 12. Qe2 a5 13. O-O-O b4 14. Qc4 O-O $1 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. exd5 bxa3 17. bxa3 Nb6 18. Qxc6 Qb7 $1 19. Qxb7 Bxb7 20. dxe5 Nxd5 21. e6 Nxe3 22. fxe3 fxe6 23. Nxe6 Rf7 $44) 9... hxg5 10. Nxg5 Rb8 $5 ({Black should be patient with} 10... b4 11. Na4 {, for the c4-square will be then at the opponent's disposal}) 11. Qd2 (11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. f4 Nc4 13. Bxc4 bxc4 14. Qe2 Qa5 $5 $132 15. O-O-O $140 Qb4 16. a3 Qxb2+ 17. Kd2 Qb7 18. Rb1 Qc7 19. Qxc4 O-O 20. Rxb8 Qxb8 21. Qxc6 Bb7 $44) (11. f4 Nh7 $5 $132) 11... Qa5 12. a3 Nf8 $1 13. b4 (13. f4 b4 14. Na2 d5 $1 15. fxe5 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 $132) 13... Qc7 14. a4 (14. Bd3 a5 15. d5 Bd7 $132) 14... a6 15. axb5 cxb5 16. Ra3 Bb7 17. Bd3 N8h7 $132) 8... O-O $1 9. Qd2 {The forcing continuations do not stop Black from striking at the center:} (9. g5 hxg5 10. Nxg5 (10. Bxg5 d5 $1 $132) (10. Rg1 exd4 $5 11. Qxd4 Nh7 12. O-O-O Qa5 13. b4 Qb6 $132) 10... Nd5 $1 {(a counterblow, which is worth remembering!)} 11. Qh5 (11. Nxd5 Bxg5) 11... Bxg5 12. Qxg5 (12. Bxg5 $6 N5f6 $15) 12... Nxe3 13. Qxe3 exd4 14. Qxd4 Qg5 $11) (9. Rg1 d5 $1 {is giving rise to immense complications:} 10. exd5 (10. g5 hxg5 11. Nxg5 Bb4 $1 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. f4 Ng6 14. e5 Bf5 $1 15. Bd3 (15. exf6 $2 Re8 $19) 15... Bxd3 16. Qxd3 d4 $1 17. Bxd4 (17. exf6 Bxc3+ 18. bxc3 dxe3 $11) 17... c5 18. O-O-O (18. Ne6 Qb6 $1 19. Nxf8 ({White can also go on with sacrifices -} 19. Nxg7 cxd4 20. Rxg6 fxg6 21. Qxg6 Bxc3+ 22. bxc3 {, after the only, but sufficient} Kh8 $1 {he has nothing else, but force a spectacular perpetual by} 23. Ne6 $1 Qxe6 24. Qh6+ Kg8 25. Qg6+ $11) 19... cxd4 20. Nxg6 dxc3 21. O-O-O Bc5 $1 22. b3 Qb4 $1 23. Kb1 Nd5 $1 24. e6 $1 fxe6 $8 25. Ne5 Bxg1 26. Qg6 $1 Qe7 $8 27. Qxg1 Rf8 $11 {The strorm is over, both sides have nicely planted knights in the center, though Black is about to eliminate the supporting f4-pawn with decent chances in the long run}) (18. exf6 cxd4 19. O-O-O dxc3 20. fxg7 Re8 $132) (18. Be3 Qxd3 19. cxd3 Nd5 20. Kd2 Ndxf4 21. Bxf4 Nxf4 22. Rg4 f6 $11) 18... cxd4 19. Ne2 {is yet another intriguing try, Black is able to give the piece back and simplify -} Qd5 20. Kb1 Nh5 21. Qf5 Nhxf4 $1 22. Nxf4 Qxe5 23. Qxe5 Nxe5 24. Nd5 Nc6 25. Nxb4 Nxb4 26. Rxd4 {and here he needs to find the precise} Na6 $1 (26... Nc6 $2 27. Rd7 $16) 27. Rdg4 (27. Rd7 Nc5) 27... f5 28. Rc4 Rac8 $11) 10... Qa5 $1 {features yet another way to pin Nc3, for the sake of the initiative Black does not hesitate to throw a pawn.} 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. g5 hxg5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Qd4 Bc5 15. Qd2 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Rb8 17. Bc4 Rb4 18. Bb3 Be7 19. e6 Rxb3 20. cxb3 (20. exd7 Rxb2 21. dxc8=Q Rxc8 22. Rg4 $1 Bb4 23. Rxb4 Rxb4 24. Ne2 Rd8 25. Qc3 Rd5 26. Kf2 Rxa4 $11) 20... fxe6 21. Qg2 ({White is finally able to castle after} 21. Nd4 Ne5 22. O-O-O {, but} c5 23. Ndb5 Nf3 {regains the exchange -} 24. Qd3 Nxg1 25. Rxg1 a6 26. Na7 Bb7 $1 {A fantastic resource, by which Black deprives the opponent of trading this bishop and establishing the other knight on e4. Here it is connected with sacrificing it, but the forced line is leading to a draw by force -} 27. Qd7 Bf6 28. Qxb7 Bxc3 29. Nc6 Bxb2+ 30. Kxb2 Qd2+ 31. Ka3 Rf2 32. Ne7+ Kf8 $8 33. Ng6+ Kg8 34. Ne7+ $11) 21... Bf6 22. O-O-O Bxc3 23. Nxg5 Bf6 24. Ne4 (24. Nxe6 $6 Qe5 $1 25. Nxf8 Nxf8 $132 {[%csl Rc1]}) 24... Qe5 25. Nxf6+ Qxf6 26. Qxc6 (26. Rgf1 {with two minor pieces for a rook Black's chances are not worse after} Qe5 27. Rxf8+ Nxf8 28. Qxc6 Qxe3+ 29. Kc2 Qf2+ 30. Kb1 Qf5+ 31. Ka2 e5 $11 {either}) 26... Ne5 27. Qc7 Ba6 28. Kb1 Rf7 29. Qd8+ Kh7 $11) 9... d5 $1 10. exd5 (10. Nxe5 {will be typically met by} Bb4 $1 11. exd5 $140 Nxd5 $132) 10... e4 $1 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Nxe4 (14. Bc4 Be6 15. Bxd5 cxd5 16. O-O-O Bb4 17. Qd4 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 Rc8 19. Qa3 Rc6 $44) ({Yet another balanced middlegame with all the heavy pieces and opposite-coloured bishop arises after} 14. O-O-O Bb4 15. Qd4 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Qa5 17. Qc5 Qxa4 18. Rd4 Qa2 19. Kd2 Be6 20. Bc4 Qb2 21. Bxd5 cxd5 22. Rb4 Qa2 $11) (14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. c3 (15. Be2 $144 Be6) 15... Be6 16. Be2 {is aiming at keeping the center closed, Black has to show his resourcefulness in order to find a way to Ke1, for example} Qb8 17. h4 Qb7 $5 ({mot recommendable is} 17... Qxe5 $2 18. Bf4 Qf6 19. g5 $16) 18. Bd4 ({in case of} 18. Kf1 {Black can switch to} Qc7 19. Bf4 (19. g5 Qxe5 20. gxh6 g6 $19) (19. Kg2 Qxe5 20. Bf4 Qf6 21. g5 $140 Qf5 $132) 19... Rab8 $44) 18... f6 $1 19. exf6 Bxf6 20. Bxf6 Rxf6 21. g5 {is beautifully countered with} e3 $1 22. fxe3 d4 $1 23. Rg1 dxc3 24. Qxc3 Rc8 25. gxf6 (25. Qd4 hxg5 26. hxg5 Rf7 $44) 25... Rxc3 26. Rxg7+ Qxg7 27. fxg7 Rxe3 28. Kd2 Rb3 29. Kc2 Rb4 $11) 14... Qc7 15. O-O-O ({It is not easy for White to decide about the future residence of his king, an alternative is} 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Nd6 Nxe3 17. Bxe6 Nxc2+ 18. Qxc2 fxe6 19. O-O Rad8 20. Qg6 Bxd6 21. Qxe6+ Kh8 22. exd6 Rxd6 23. Qe5 Qb8 24. Rae1 (24. Qc3 Rdf6 $44) 24... Rd2 25. Qxb8 Rxb8 $11) 15... Qxe5 16. Qd4 Qc7 {The position resembles a line with 9.0-0-0 in the Dragon, in which Black sacrifices his e7-pawn. Here, regarding the weakening with a2-a4, he will have extra possibilities.} 17. Bc4 ({No better is to part with the bishop -} 17. g5 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 hxg5 19. Nxg5 Rb8 20. Rg1 Bf5 {[%cal Ge7f6]} 21. Bc4 Bf6 22. b3 g6 23. Ne4 Bxe4 24. Qxe4 Kg7 25. Bd3 Kh8 $44 {[%csl Rc1,Gf6]}) 17... Rd8 18. Bxd5 (18. Nc5 Qb6 $11) (18. g5 hxg5 19. Bxg5 c5 $1 20. Qd2 Nb6 $1 21. Qe2 Bb7 22. Bxe7 Qxe7 23. f3 Nxa4 $11) 18... Be6 (18... cxd5 {is playable as well, the vulnerability of the a4-pawn is telling after} 19. Qc3 Qd7 20. Nc5 Bxc5 21. Bxc5 Qxa4 22. b3 Qc6 $14) 19. Nc3 (19. Qc3 Bxd5 20. f3 Rab8 $44) 19... cxd5 20. Rhg1 Bf6 21. Bf4 (21. Qc5 Qh2 $1 22. Rh1 Qb8 $132 {[%cal Gd8c8]}) 21... Bxd4 22. Bxc7 Bxf2 23. Bxd8 Bxg1 24. Ba5 ({In case of} 24. Rxg1 Rxd8 25. Nb5 Bd7 26. Rd1 {Black can go for a rook ending or keep the bishop, intending a timely h6-h5 break, e.g.} a6 27. Nc3 Be6 28. Ne2 g5 29. Nd4 Kg7 $132 {[%cal Gh6h5]}) 24... Be3+ 25. Kb1 d4 26. Nb5 Bd7 $1 {Pointing once again at the a4-pawn, the endgame is balanced -} 27. Nxd4 Bxa4 28. b3 (28. Nf5 Bc5 29. Rd5 Bf8 $11) 28... Be8 29. Kb2 (29. c4 Bxd4 30. Rxd4 Bc6 {is similar.}) 29... Bxd4+ 30. Rxd4 Bc6 31. c4 f6 $11 *

