k, he is enjoying 3 pawns for the piece, including a whole phalanx on the kingside -} 20. Ka2 (20. Bf4 Rhe8) 20... f6 $44) (7. Qe2 {is bizarre-looking, but we are yet to see (after Bc1-e3) lines, in which Qd1-d2 has tactical drawbacks because of the f3-square. Let us assune for now that the idea is to avoid such trouble, but Black can steal that luxury by questioning the central d4-pawn with the energetic} Qb6 $1 (7... b5 8. a3 a5 9. h4 $140 Ba6 10. Qe3 h5 11. gxh5 {with mutual chances}) 8. d5 ({the pawn will be doomed here, but the exchange} 8. dxe5 {is not a solution in the view of} Nxe5 $1 9. h3 $140 Be6 $36) 8... cxd5 9. exd5 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gf6d5,Ga5e1] Black's next big point!} 10. Nd4 (10. Bd2 Nxd5 11. Nd4 {transposes}) 10... Nxd5 11. Bd2 N7f6 12. Rg3 (12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Nb5 Qc6 14. Bg2 e4 $132) (12. O-O-O Qb6 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Nf5 Be6 15. Bg2 Rc8 $132) 12... Qc5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Nb3 Qc7 {Here is a sample line, in which White succeeds in regaining the pawn -} 15. Bg2 Be6 16. Qb5+ Qd7 17. Qxd7+ Kxd7 18. Rd3 Nb6 19. Nc5+ Ke7 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. Bxb7 Rb8 22. Ba6 g5 $132) (7. h4 {, unlike 7.a4, looks consistent, but it can be challenged by} exd4 $1 {as well, as follows:} 8. Qxd4 {is typically met by} (8. Nxd4 {will be once again answered with} Ne5 {(d5; xg4) and now:} 9. g5 (9. Be2 d5 $1 10. exd5 Bb4 11. dxc6 (11. Bd2 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Nxd5 $11) 11... O-O $44) 9... hxg5 10. hxg5 Nfg4 $1 {is a reminiscence of the sacrifices on this square from above, here we are going to enter amyriad of repetitions, for example} 11. f4 (11. Be2 Nh2 12. f4 Qb6 {will just ranspose, while}) (11. f3 $6 {can end catastrophically after} Nh2 $1) 11... Qb6 $1 12. Be2 Nh2 $1 13. Rg3 ({a reasonable decision to reconcile himself with the draw; the tactics are working in Black's favour after} 13. Be3 $6 Neg4 14. Qd2 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Rh3 $132) 13... Nhg4 14. Rg1 Nh2 $11) 8... Qb6 $1 9. Be3 (9. Qxb6 axb6 10. g5 Nh5 11. Be3 b5 $132) 9... Qxb2 ({such principled play is not without a reason; fully playable 