mysterious} Rf8 $1 {, to which White should go ahead with} 17. e5 (17. Kb1 Be6 $132 {reveals the main point behind the previous move}) 17... d5 18. Bxd5 cxd5 19. Nxd5 Qc5 20. Qe2 {, threatening 21.b4. A possible reaction to it is to castle in return for the extra piece by} Bd7 21. f5 O-O-O 22. b4 $140 Bb5 23. Qh2 Qc4 24. Nxe7+ Kb8 25. e6+ Ka8 $132) 13... Qe7 $1 {A step towards castling to the long wth continuous protection of Bh4.} (13... O-O 14. Be2 Nhf6 15. f5 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Bg5 17. Qh3 $40) (13... g5 14. Bh3 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 gxf4 16. Qf3 Bxh3 17. Qxh5 {is, similarly to the course of the leading text, resulting in a battle of two minor pieces against a rook with pawn(s), but this version seems to favour White -} Bf2 18. Qxh3 Bxg1 19. Rxg1 Qd7 $140 20. Qh5 O-O-O 21. Rf1) 14. Be2 Ng3 $1 {The more active of the two jumps, which leads to an irrational position will the minor at the edge of the board.} (14... Nhf6 15. e5 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 g6 $13 {is the other critical direction.}) 15. Bxg4 {Providing his queen with an access to the h2-square.} (15. Bd3 f5 $1 ({Black can also release the tension by exchanges -} 15... Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Nf5 17. Nxf5 Bxf5 18. Rxg7 Bf6 19. Rg2 Be6) 16. exf5 (16. e5 O-O $132) 16... Nxe3 17. Rde1 Ngxf5 18. Bxf5 Bxe1 19. Rxe1 Nxf5 20. Rxe7+ Kxe7 21. Ne4 Rf8 $11) (15. Nf3 {is an obliging decision, after} Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 {Black is already 3 pawns up and therefore does not mind to get a rook for his remaining minor pieces after 17.Rxg4, here are White's sharper alternatives to it:} 17. Bd4 (17. Nxh4 Nxe3 {will cost the life of this knight, but at a high price:} 18. Rde1 (18. Bh5 Nxc2 $1 19. Qxc2 (19. Bf3 Na3+ 20. Ka1 Nc2+ $11) 19... Qxc2+ 20. Kxc2 g6 21. Be2 Kd7 22. Rde1 Kc7 $44) 18... Qxf4 {(here is a fourth one!)} 19. Bh5 O-O 20. Rxe3 (20. Qxe3 Qxe3 21. Rxe3 Be6 $132) 20... Qxh4 {and Black will obtain plenty of material for the queen -} 21. Reg3 g5 22. Rxg5+ hxg5 23. Rxg5+ Kh7 24. Bf3 Be6 25. Rh5+ Qxh5 26. Bxh5 Rfd8 $132) 17... Bf6 $1 18. Bd3 Qxf3 19. Rde1+ Ne5 ({a risky-looking answer, but this must be Black's choice if he believes in the viability of his position and does not want to play without his queen. Otherwise, worth checking is} 19... Be6 20. Be4 Qh3 21. Rh1 Qxh1 22. Rxh1 Rd8) 20. fxe5 Bxe5 21. Bxe5 dxe5 22. Rxe5+ Be6 23. Rxe6+ fxe6 24. Bg6+ Ke7 25. Qb4+ Kd8 26. Qxb7 (26. Qd6+ Kc8 27. Qxe6+ Kc7 28. Qe7+ Kc8 29. Qe6+ $11) 26... Rc8 27. Qxa7 Rf8 28. Qd4+ Qd5 29. Qxg7 Qd6 30. Re1 Rc7 31. Qxh6 Rb7 $11) ({About} 15. Rxg3 Bxg3 16. Bxg4 Bxg4 {see 16.Rxg4 below.}) 15... Bxg4 16. Rc1 ({White can go for a hunt of the bishops by means of} 16. Rxg3 Bxg3 17. Rg1 Qh4 18. Nce2 ({Black would be glad to liquidate to a pleasant endgame like the one after} 18. Qg2 Be1 $1 19. Qxg4 $140 Qxg4 20. Rxg4 Bxc3 21. bxc3 g6 $15) 18... Bh2 $1 19. Rh1 {, the best reaction to which seems to be} d5 $1 20. Nc3 (20. exd5 O-O $132) 20... dxe4 21. Rxh2 Qe7 22. Qf2 h5 $132) (16. Rde1 {threatens 17,Bf2, so Black is obliged to grab more material -} Nxe4 $1 17. Nxe4 Bxe1 18. Rxe1 O-O 19. f5 $1 Qxe4 20. Bxh6 Qxe1+ 21. Qxe1 gxh6 22. Qh4 h5 $1 {with perpetual in the air -} 23. Qg5+ (23. Qf6 $144) 23... Kh7 24. Qf6 Rae8 $11 25. Ne6 fxe6 ({a draw is the likely outcome in case of} 25... Rxe6 $5 26. fxe6 Bxe6 27. Qg5 $140 Bg4 28. Qe7 Rg8 29. Qxf7+ Rg7 30. Qf6 d5) 26. Qg6+ Kh8 27. Qh6+) (16. Bf2 Bxd1 17. Qxd1 O-O-O 18. Bxg3 Bxg3 19. Rxg3 $132) 16... h5 {Supporting Bg4 at least, though there is no way back for the other two stranded pieces.} 17. Qh2 (17. Bf2 $6 {must be evaluated as imprecise in the view of the neat shot} Ne2 $1 18. Rxg4 Nxc3+ 19. Qxc3 hxg4 20. Nf5 Qf6 21. Bxh4 ({Black has, apart from the potentially dangerous g4-pawn, much material up, a part of which can be always returned -} 21. Bd4 Qg6 22. Qb4 O-O-O $1 23. Bxa7 Qe6 24. Bb6 Bf6 25. Qa3 Kd7 26. Rd1 d5 $132) 21... Qxc3 22. bxc3 Kd7 {with decent chances -} 23. Rd1 d5 $132) 17... f5 $1 18. exf5 ({Here} 18. Bf2 {is more to the point, Black will get 3 pawns for a piece, moreover, the created passed one after} fxe4 {is going to play a significant role:} 19. Bxg3 (19. Rce1 d5 $132) (19. f5 O-O $1 20. Bxg3 Bxg3 21. Qxg3 Rae8 22. Rce1 d5 23. Nd1 Bxf5 24. Ne3 Bd7 25. Qc7 Bc8 26. Qxe7 Rxe7 27. Rg5 g6 28. c4 Kh7 29. cxd5 cxd5 30. Reg1 (30. Nxd5 Rd7 $44) 30... Rg7 31. Rxd5 h4 32. Re5 h3 33. Ne6 Bxe6 34. Rxe6 Rf3 35. Rxe4 Rgf7 $44) 19... Bf6 $1 20. Nce2 (20. Qd2 e3 21. Qd3 O-O 22. Ne4 Rae8 23. Nxf6+ Qxf6 24. Rce1 Qe7 25. Qc3 c5 26. Qb3+ Kh8 27. Ne2 Rf5 28. Nc3 Qe6 $44) 20... O-O-O 21. f5 Rhe8 22. Bf4 Rd7 23. Rcd1 Qf7 $132) 18... O-O (18... O-O-O $2 19. Bf2 $16) 19. Rxg3 {The expected transformation to two minor pieces for a rook and a pawn or two.} ({The same happens after} 19. Bf2 Qf6 $1 20. Rxg3 ({alternatively, after} 20. Ne6 Nxf5 21. Nxf8 Rxf8 {Black has enough compensation for the exchange -} 22. Ne4 Qe6 23. Rce1 Bd8 $44) 20... Bxg3 21. Qxg3 Rae8 22. Ne6 Rf7 23. Ng5 Rfe7 24. Bxa7 Qxf5 $132) 19... Bxg3 20. Qxg3 Rae8 21. Bd2 ({The idea to oppose along the e-file by} 21. Re1 Qf6 22. Ne6 Rf7 23. Bc1 d5 24. b3 {is requiring urgent measures from Black, such as} Rfe7 $1 25. Ba3 Qxf5 26. Bxe7 (26. Re5 Qf6) 26... Rxe7 27. Ng5 Rxe1+ 28. Qxe1 Qxf4 {, with 3 pawns for the piece and a probable repetition after} 29. Qe8+ Qf8 30. Qe5 Qf1+ 31. Kb2 Qf5 32. Qb8+ Qc8 33. Qe5 Qf5 $11) (21. Bf2 Rf7 $132) 21... Qf6 $1 22. Nf3 (22. Ne6 Rf7 23. Ne4 Qxf5 24. Nxg7 {is leading by force to a balanced position -} Qxe4 25. Nxe8 Qxe8 26. Bc3 $132 {, in which the extra pawn is compensated by the safer king}) (22. Qf2 d5 $132) (22. Qd3 c5 23. Ndb5 Qxf5 24. Qc4+ Qe6 25. Nxd6 Rd8 $132 {and, after the trade of the queens, Black's chances are not worse due mainly to the passed h5-pawn.}) 22... Rf7 ({Or} 22... Bxf5 {at first.}) 23. Rg1 Bxf5 24. a3 Bg4 25. Nh2 Bd7 $132 *

