1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 Nxg4 $1 (5... h6 {is lilely to transpose to the Chapters about 5.Rg1 and 5.h3.}) 6. Rg1 Ngf6 7. Bc4 (7. Be3 c6 8. Qd2 {is apparently aiming at castling to the long, though the c4-square will be no longer accessible for Bf1 after} b5 9. O-O-O $140 Qa5 $1 10. dxe5 ({it is hard to say whether Black is really planning b5-b4 on the next move, but after} 10. a3 {he can still speculate with, for instance} Rb8 11. Kb1 Qc7 $1 (11... b4 12. axb4 Qxb4 13. b3 $13) 12. d5 b4 13. axb4 Rxb4 $132) ({ignoring that push with} 10. Kb1 {may result in a two-pawns deficit after} b4 11. Ne2 Nxe4 12. Qe1 (12. Qd3 $6 d5 $17) {, though, regarding the precarious location of Ke8, Black has to come up with the precise} 12... Ndf6 $1 13. Nd2 Be6 14. Nc1 Nxd2+ (14... Qc7 $5) 15. Bxd2 exd4 (15... e4 16. Bxb4 Qh5 $132) 16. Bxb4 Qe5 17. Bg2 Rc8 18. Ne2 d5 $132) 10... dxe5 11. Kb1 {seems to be White's best move order:} Rb8 $5 ({here} 11... b4 {contains certain risks, for example} 12. Na4 $1 g6 $1 (12... Qxa4 $2 13. Nxe5 $18 Be7 $140 14. Nxf7 $1) 13. Bc4 Ba6 $13 {with very sharp play}) 12. Bh3 Qc7 $1 (12... b4 $6 {is once again running into} 13. Na4 $1) 13. Bg5 (13. Bxd7+ Nxd7 14. b3 (14. Nh4 b4 15. Na4 g6 16. f4 Be7 17. Nf3 Nf6 18. Nxe5 O-O $132) 14... g6 15. Ng5 $1 (15. h4 h6 $132) 15... h6 ({urging White to sacrifice a piece and open files against Ke8; it is worth checking} 15... Bc5 $5 {, trying to keep the position closed and even to castle}) 16. Ne6 fxe6 17. Rxg6 Nb6 $1 18. Bxh6 Bxh6 19. Rxh6 Rg8 $1 20. Qe3 Qe7 21. Qh3 Rb7 22. Qh5+ Qf7 23. Qxe5 Qg7 24. Qh5+ ({White can claim a definite compensation after} 24. Rxe6+ Bxe6 25. Qxe6+ Re7 26. Qxc6+ Kf8 27. Nxb5 Rd7 28. Nd4 {as well - there is no safe shelter for the king, e.g.} Qe7 29. Qh6+ Ke8 30. Qh5+ Qf7 31. Qe5+ $11) 24... Qf7 25. Qe5 (25. Qc5 Rd7 26. Qxc6 Kd8 $132) 25... Qg7 $11) (13. Ne2 {is inviting Black to take the bull by the horns -} Nxe4 14. Bxd7+ Bxd7 15. Qd3 Bf5 $1 16. Nh4 (16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Bf4 {will lead to simplifications and equality after} Nc3+ $1 18. Qxc3 Qxc3 19. bxc3 Rc8 20. Nd4 Be6 21. Rde1 $1) 16... Nxf2 $1 17. Qxf5 Nxd1 18. Rxd1 Be7 19. Nf3 f6 $132 {Black has objectively more material, but he has to tread carefully in the view of the exposed light squares in his camp, for example} 20. Nh4 ({or} 20. Qh5+ g6 21. Qh6 Rd8 22. Rf1 Bf8 23. Qh4 Be7 24. Qh6 $140 Bf8) 20... Rd8 21. Rf1 g6 22. Nxg6 hxg6 23. Qxg6+ Kd7 24. Qf5+ Ke8 25. Qg6+ Kd7 $11) 13... b4 14. Ne2 (14. Na4 $6 {is not so strong here because of} h6 $1 15. Bxf6 (15. Bh4 $6 {is provoking} g5 16. Bg3 Nxe4 {and} 17. Qd4 $5 Nxg3 18. Bxd7+ Bxd7 19. Nxe5 {is effectively parried by} Ne2 $1 20. Qe3 Be6 21. Qxe2 Rb5 $17) 15... Nxf6 16. Bxc8 Rxc8 17. Qe2 g6 18. Qc4 c5 19. Qb5+ Ke7 $5 20. c3 $140 Rb8 21. Qa6 Bg7 $15) {should be answered with the same} 14... h6 $1 {and now:} 15. Bxf6 (15. Bh4 c5 16. Bg3 Be7 17. Qe3 a5 $1 18. Nf4 (18. Nh4 {is a preparation for both Nh4-f5 and f2-f4; a radical measure against the latter is} g5 $5 19. Bxd7+ (19. Nf5 Nb6 20. Ng7+ Kf8 21. Bxc8 Qxc8 22. Nf5 Nc4 23. Qd3 Qe6 24. f4 a4 $132) 19... Bxd7 20. Nf5 Nh5 $1 21. Rd5 (21. Nxe7 Kxe7 22. Rd5 f6 23. h4 Kf7 24. Qf3 Kg6 $132) {and here} 21... Nf4 $1 {is investing a couple of pawns for completing the mobilization with good prospects on the queenside after} 22. Nxe7 Kxe7 23. Rxc5 Qd6 24. Rxa5 Rhc8 $132) (18. Bxd7+ Nxd7 19. Rxd7 {looks dangerous, but Black should be able to hold after} Qxd7 20. Nxe5 (20. Bxe5 Rb6 21. Rxg7 Bb7 $132) 20... Qb5 $1 {, for example} 21. b3 (21. Nf4 c4 22. Nd5 Rb7 $15) (21. Nc4 Be6 22. Nd6+ Bxd6 23. Bxd6 Rc8 $132) 21... a4 22. Nxf7 Kxf7 (22... axb3 $5 23. Nxh8 bxc2+ 24. Kc1 Ra8 $132) 23. bxa4 Qxa4 24. Qf3+ Bf6 25. Bxb8 Be6 26. Nc1 b3 27. Nxb3 Rxb8 28. e5 c4 29. Rxg7+ Kxg7 30. Qxf6+ Kh7 31. Qe7+ $11) 18... exf4 19. Bxf4 Qb7 20. Bxb8 Nxb8 21. Ne5 {is also declaring a clear intention to break through, a patience and accuracy is required from Black, e.g.} Bxh3 22. Qxh3 Nc6 23. Nxc6 Qxc6 24. Qg3 Qb7 $1 25. e5 (25. Qxg7 Rg8 26. Qxh6 Rxg1 27. Rxg1 Qxe4 28. Qh8+ Kd7 29. Qb8 Bd6 30. Rd1 Qe5 $11) 25... Nh5 26. Qg4 g6 27. e6 Qc6 $1 {(curiously enough, the best Black's defensive moves are connected with his queen moving between b7 and c6!)} 28. Rde1 (28. Rge1 c4 $132) 28... Rf8 29. exf7+ Rxf7 30. Re6 Qf3 31. Qxg6 (31. Qxf3 Rxf3 32. Rge1 Rf7 33. Rxg6 Rf6 $11) 31... Nf4 32. Qg8+ Rf8 33. Rxe7+ Kxe7 34. Re1+ Ne2 35. Qc4 Kd6 36. Qxe2 Qxe2 37. Rxe2 $11) 15... Nxf6 16. Bxc8 Rxc8 17. Nc1 $1 c5 18. Nd3 Rd8 {is, whilst creating a threat for c5-c4, opposing in time on the open d-file:} 19. Qe2 (19. c4 {resumes the attack at the central pawn, Black is well-advised not to stick to it and finish his development -} g6 $1 20. Nfxe5 Bg7 21. f4 O-O 22. Qe3 Rfe8 23. Qxc5 (23. Nxc5 Nh5 $1 $132) 23... Qxc5 24. Nxc5 Rc8 25. Ncd3 a5 $44) 19... Nd7 $1 20. Nfxe5 ({with the insertion of} 20. b3 g6 {the similar line} 21. Ndxe5 Nxe5 22. Nxe5 Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Qxe5 24. Qb5+ Ke7 25. Rd5 {can come to the same outcome, but in a simpler manner by} Qc3 26. e5 $1 Qe1+ $11) 20... Nxe5 (20... c4 $5 21. Qh5 g6 22. Rxg6 Nxe5 23. Re6+ Be7 24. Nxe5 Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 fxe6 26. Qh5+ Kd8 27. Nf7+ Kc8 28. Nxh8 Qd6 $11) 21. Nxe5 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Qxe5 23. Qb5+ Ke7 24. Rd5 (24. Qb7+ Kf6 25. f4 Qxf4 26. Qa6+ Kg5 $8 27. Rg1+ Kh4 $8 28. Qe2 Bd6 29. Qe1+ Kh5 30. Qe2+ $11) 24... Qxe4 25. Qb7+ Kf6 26. Rd6+ Ke5 27. f4+ Kxf4 28. Qxf7+ Kg4 29. h3+ Kh4 $1 30. Qf2+ Kh5 31. Qf7+ Kh4 $11) 7... h6 $1 {This prophylaxis against Nf3-g5 is more or less necessary.} (7... exd4 8. Qxd4 Nb6 {is another way to parry the attack at the f7-square by chasing Bc4:} 9. Be2 (9. Bb3 Bg4 $1 10. Qd3 d5 $1 11. Ne5 (11. e5 Qe7 $132) 11... Bh5 12. Bf4 g6 $13) {overprotects Nf3, White's lead in development after} 9... g6 10. Bg5 Bg7 11. O-O-O $44 {with the threat of e4-e5 is really frightening.}) 8. Be3 {A natural continuation, which can also be played in few moves:} (8. Qe2 {must be a sign for castl;ing to the long.} c6 {is the usual answer:} 9. Bb3 {seems to anticipate the march of the b7-pawn, but Black can shift his attention to the center by} (9. Be3 {can be challenged by} b5 10. Bb3 Ba6 {with c6-c5 in mind:} 11. dxe5 (11. d5 c5 12. a4 b4 13. Qxa6 bxc3 14. bxc3 Nxe4 $132) (11. Nd2 Qc8 $1 12. Qf3 b4 13. Ne2 c5 14. d5 ({White's knights are far away from the d5-square in case of} 14. dxc5 dxc5 15. Nc4 Qc6 $132) 14... Nb6 $132) 11... dxe5 12. Nd2 Qa5 13. Qf3 b4 14. Ne2 g6 15. O-O-O Bc5 16. Bxf7+ Kxf7 17. Nc4 Bxe3+ 18. fxe3 Bxc4 19. Rxd7+ Ke8 20. Qxf6 Kxd7 21. Rxg6 Qc5 22. Rg7+ Ke8 (22... Kc8 23. Qf5+ Kb8 24. Qd7 Qb6 25. Qd6+ $11) 23. Qg6+ Kd8 $11) 9... Qe7 $5 (9... exd4 10. Nxd4 Nc5 11. Be3 Qe7 12. f3 g6 13. O-O-O Bg7 $13) (9... b5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. a4 $36) 10. Be3 exd4 $1 11. Bxd4 (11. Nxd4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Qxe4 13. O-O-O Nc5 14. Qd2 Bd7 {[%cal Ge8c8]} 15. Rde1 Nxb3+ 16. axb3 O-O-O 17. Bg5 Qxe1+ 18. Rxe1 hxg5 $44) 11... Ne5 12. Nd2 (12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Be3 Be6 14. O-O-O Bxb3 15. axb3 Qe6 16. f4 g6 $132) 12... g5 $1 {A multifunctional move, which can come as a shock to the opponent. This pawn is no longer a target, secures the excellent Ne5 and, we should remember that Black is a pawn up!} 13. O-O-O (13. h4 g4) 13... Rg8 14. Qe3 (14. Kb1 Rg6) (14. Nc4 Bg4 $1 15. Rxg4 Nfxg4 16. h3 Nf6 17. Bxe5 dxe5 18. Nd6+ Qxd6 19. Rxd6 Bxd6 20. Qf3 $132 Ke7 $140 21. Ne2 g4 22. hxg4 Rxg4 23. Ng3 Rf4 24. Qe3 h5 25. Nf5+ Kd7 {and it is sensible to go for the repetition} 26. Nxd6 Kxd6 27. Qd2+ Kc7 28. Qa5+ Kd6 29. Qb4+ Kc7 30. Qa5+ Kd6 $11) 14... Rg6 15. Kb1 Nfg4 16. Qg3 (16. Qe2 b5) 16... b5 17. h3 Nf6 $132) (8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Be3 c6 {transposes to the main text}) (8. a4 {is quite possible, though it is usually not preceding} c6 {, so:} 9. Be3 ({White's last two moves could be played in reversed order;} 9. a5 {is of independent significance, Black can be also strict with} g5 $5 {, returning the etra pawn, but liquidating to a safe ending in the line} 10. dxe5 Nxe5 ({avoiding the crafty trap} 10... dxe5 $2 11. Bxg5 $1 $40) 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Bxf7+ Ke7 $132) {can be met in a very concrete manner -} 9... Qa5 $5 10. Nd2 h5 $1 {[%cal Gf6g4] and now:} 11. f3 (11. h3 exd4 12. Nb3 Qb4 {is filling more fuel into the fire -} 13. Qxd4 c5 14. Qd3 Ne5 15. Bb5+ Bd7 16. Qe2 O-O-O 17. f4 Nc6 18. O-O-O a6 19. e5 axb5 20. exf6 bxa4 21. Nd5 Qe4 22. Nd2 $1 Qxd5 23. Nc4 Qe6 24. fxg7 Bxg7 25. Rxg7 Nd4 26. Rxd4 $1 cxd4 27. f5 Qe7 28. Rxf7 Qh4 $1 {It is vital to preserve the d4-pawn on the board, under the circumstances White must be satisfied with the draw after} 29. Nb6+ Kc7 30. Qc4+ (30. Rxd7+ Kxb6 $1 31. Rxb7+ Kxb7 32. Qb5+ Kc7 33. Qc4+ $11) 30... Kb8 31. Qb4 Qe4 32. Qxd6+ Ka7 33. Qxd4 Qxd4 34. Bxd4 Be8 35. Nd5+ Kb8 36. Be5+ Ka7 $11) ({in reply to} 11. Bb3 {Black can insist on with} Qb4 {, which is in fact an offer of a p[ositional queen sacrifice in case of} 12. a5 ({White can think twice and go for an early repetition with} 12. Na2 Qa5 $11) 12... exd4 13. Ra4 Qxa4 14. Nxa4 dxe3 15. fxe3 Ne5 $44) 11... Qb4 $1 {is again messing the things up, after} 12. a5 {Black has the consequent} d5 $1 13. exd5 cxd5 {, which is like burning all the bridges behind him, but with a reson:} 14. dxe5 ({the position remains more or less balanced after} 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 exd4 16. Bf2 Nc5 17. a6 Bd6 18. Qe2+ (18. Rxg7 Be6) 18... Be6 19. axb7 Rb8 $132) 14... Nxe5 15. Bxd5 Qxb2 {is much sharper -} 16. Nde4 Bb4 $1 17. Rb1 Bxc3+ 18. Ke2 Qa3 19. Bc5 $1 Qxa5 20. Nd6+ Kd8 {An extremely wild position with walking kings has arisen. Nevertheless, it is no wonder that the engines are indicating paths to a draw in juat few moves!} 21. Rb5 Qc7 22. Bxb7 Nfd7 $1 23. Bxc8 ({the same perpetual occurs in the end of the line} 23. Qd5 Rb8 24. f4 Nf6 25. Nxf7+ Ke8 26. Nd6+ Kd8 $11 {as well}) 23... Rxc8 24. Nb7+ Ke8 25. Nd6+ Kd8 $11) (8. Bb3 c6 9. Qe2 {- 8.Qe2}) 8... c6 9. dxe5 {It seems that White cannot do without opening the center for long.} (9. Qd3 b5 10. Bb3 {is on the verge of transposing to the main text, e.g.} Qa5 ({or} 10... Ba6) 11. O-O-O Ba6 12. dxe5 dxe5 {etc.}) (9. a4 {is similar to 8.a4 and may even transpose to the line with 12.a4, see below}) (9. Qe2 {- 8.Qe2}) (9. Bb3 b5 10. dxe5 (10. Qd3 {on this and on the next move can lead to the leading line}) 10... dxe5 11. a4 b4 12. Nb1 Ba6 13. Nbd2 Bc5 14. Bxc5 Nxc5 15. Rxg7 (15. Nxe5 O-O 16. Qf3 Qd6 17. Qf4 Nxb3 18. Nxb3 Nd7 19. Ng6 Qxf4 20. Nxf4 Rae8 $132) 15... Nxb3 16. Nxb3 Nxe4 17. Nxe5 Ng5 $1 18. Nc5 Qxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Bc8 {and} 20. Ned7 {may lead to an amusing repetition after} Bxd7 21. Rxd7 Kf8 22. Ne6+ Ke8 23. Nc5 Kf8 $11) 9... dxe5 10. Qd3 (10. Qe2 b5 11. Bb3 Ba6 {does not differ.}) 10... b5 11. Bb3 Qa5 (11... Ba6 {is also probably the same.}) 12. O-O-O ({Instead,} 12. a4 {opens a new front -} Ba6 (12... b4 $5 13. Nb1 Nc5 14. Bxc5 Qxc5 15. Nbd2 Bg4 $1 16. Nc4 Rd8 17. Qe2 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Rd4 19. Qf5 $1 {A reminder of the risks with Ke8, which is stuck in the center for long.} Rxe4+ 20. Ne3 Rxe3+ 21. fxe3 Qxe3+ 22. Kf1 Qf4+ 23. Qxf4 exf4 24. Re1+ Kd7 $44) 13. Ke2 b4 14. Nb5 O-O-O $1 15. Nxa7+ Kc7 $5 (15... Kb7 16. Bc4 Bxc4 17. Qxc4 Bc5 {is unclear, after} 18. Bxc5 Nxc5 {White is obliged to give Na7 for several pawns -} 19. Nxc6 Kxc6 20. Nxe5+ Kc7 21. Rxg7 {and it looks easier for him to play, but} Rhe8 $1 {shows that Ke2 is not in safety either}) 16. Bc4 (16. Nb5+ Kc8 {repeats}) 16... Bb7 17. Nb5+ Kc8 18. Rgd1 $5 {Yet another try to continue the game, even though there are still plenty of perpetuals or repetitions in the air.} Bc5 19. Nd6+ Bxd6 20. Qxd6 Nxe4 21. Qe7 Nef6 (21... Ba6 $5) 22. Bxf7 (22. Qxf7 Nd5) 22... Qc7 23. a5 Nd5 24. Bxd5 cxd5 25. a6 Bxa6+ 26. Rxa6 Qc4+ 27. Ke1 Qxa6 28. Rxd5 Qa1+ 29. Ke2 (29. Rd1 Qa5) 29... Qa6+ $11) (12. Nd2 $144 Ba6 13. O-O-O) 12... Ba6 13. Nd2 $1 (13. Ne2 $6 {allows} c5 $1 14. c4 b4 {and Black has successfully locked the position and Bb3 in particular -} 15. Ng3 g6 $17) 13... Rd8 ({The other way to bring Ra8 into play is} 13... O-O-O {, which is giving the extra pawn back -} 14. Bxf7 {, but Black has decent chances after the forced} Nc5 15. Qf1 b4 16. Qh3+ Kb8 17. Ncb1 Qc7 {, for instance} 18. Bc4 Bc8 19. Qf3 Ne6 $132) (13... Rb8 $5) 14. Qf1 {A reasonable retreat.} ({No better is} 14. Kb1 {, when} Nc5 {forces} 15. Qf1 {anyway, Black is in order after} b4 16. Nc4 Nxb3 17. axb3 Rxd1+ 18. Nxd1 Bxc4 19. bxc4 (19. Qxc4 $6 Qb5 $1) 19... g6 20. f4 Be7 $132) 14... g6 15. a3 ({It might be not that evident at first glance, but} 15. f4 $2 {is seriously weakening the e3-square and Black can capitalize on it by means of} b4 16. Nc4 Bc5 $1 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 18. Nd6+ Qxd6 19. Qxa6 Qc5 20. Na4 Qe3+ 21. Kb1 O-O 22. Qxc6 Qxe4 $17) 15... b4 $5 {A tempting push, though here Black will have to part with his Ba6.} ({Alternatively, Black can stick to a dark-squared strategy by} 15... Bc5 $5 16. Qh3 Bxe3 17. Qxe3 b4 18. axb4 Qxb4 19. f4 Qc5 $132) 16. Nc4 bxc3 17. Nxa5 cxb2+ 18. Kxb2 Bxf1 19. Rgxf1 Rc8 20. f4 ({Trying to open the position for his bishops rather than} 20. f3 Nc5 $11) 20... Bg7 (20... Ng4 {is possible, but after} 21. Bxa7 exf4 22. Rxf4 Nge5 23. Bd4 {Black will have to go for the slightly awkward} Rh7 $11) 21. fxe5 (21. f5 g5 $132) 21... Nxe5 22. Bd4 Nfg4 {Here is the main difference to the abovementioned line with 20....Ng4 - the knight, which is supporting the planted one in the center, plays an active role in the events. This is illustrated by the following forced line - White is restoring the material balance, but the position is significantly simplified.} 23. Bxf7+ Nxf7 24. Bxg7 Ne3 25. Bxh8 Nxh8 26. Kc3 Nf7 27. Nc4 Nxd1+ 28. Rxd1 Ke7 $11 *

