1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Be3 ({The more active development of this bishop} 7. Bg5 {deserves to be questioned with} h6 ({indeed, Black can start with} 7... c6) 8. Bh4 c6 9. a4 (9. Re1 b5 10. Bf1 Bb7 11. a4 a6 $11) 9... a5 10. Re1 {and Black can point at the absence of Bc1 from its wing by} Qb6 $11) (7. Qe2 c6 ({the preliminary} 7... exd4 $5 8. Nxd4 $140 c6 {is also good enough}) 8. dxe5 ({White should already reckon with the X-ray along the e-file after both} 8. Rd1 $6 exd4 $1 9. Nxd4 Re8 $15 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ge7f8,Gd6d5,Ge8e2]}) ({and} 8. a4 exd4 $1 9. Nxd4 Re8 $11 {[%cal Ge7f8]}) 8... dxe5 (8... Nxe5 $144 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Rd1 Qa5 $11) 9. a4 Qc7 10. Be3 a5 $11) (7. h3 c6 8. a4 {transposes to the next Chapter.}) 7... exd4 $5 ({The last comment belongs to} 7... c6 8. a4 {as well.}) 8. Qxd4 {White is facing a wide choice.} (8. Nxd4 Ne5 9. Be2 ({dubious is} 9. Bb3 $6 {in the view of} c5 10. Nf3 Bg4 11. Bf4 {(a second move with the same piece is not a good sign)} Nfd7 $15) 9... d5 {seems to equalize by force -} 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 {due to the small firework} 12. Nf5 Nf3+ $1 13. Bxf3 Qxf5 $11) (8. Bxd4 Nb6 $1 {is yet another way for Black's spring to stretch:} 9. Bd3 (9. Bb3 {is a signal for} c5 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Qd3 {White has had to part with Bd4 and it is arguable how strong his control over the d5-square is, given the powerful Bf6. Black, in his turn, can even force matters by} c4 $5 ({a tempting forcing continuation in comparison to the restrained options} 11... Bd7) ({and} 11... Re8) 12. Bxc4 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Bg4 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 14. Qd3 ({White cannot keep his queenside intact after} 14. Nd4 {as well, for example} Qb6 15. Nb3 Rac8 16. Qd3 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Qc7 $11) 14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 (15. Qxc3 Rc8 16. Qb3 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Rc5 $44) 15... Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Qa5 17. Rfd1 Rac8 18. Rd3 h6 $44) (9. Be2 {does not discourage} c5 10. Be3 (10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. a4 Bxc3 12. bxc3 d5 $11) 10... Be6 (10... d5 $5 11. e5 Ne8 12. Bf4 Nc7 $11) 11. Ng5 Bd7 12. a4 a5 {[%cal Gd7c6]} 13. Re1 Bc6 $11) 9... c5 $1 10. Be3 (10. Bxf6 {is a concession again, after} Bxf6 {Black can meet} 11. a4 {with} Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bd7 $5 13. a5 $140 Na4 $132 {[%cal Gd8a5,Ga4c3]}) 10... d5 $1 {is critical, the position after} 11. e5 d4 12. Bxd4 (12. exf6 $144 Bxf6) 12... cxd4 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. Ne4 Bg4 15. h3 Bh5 {is already resembling the Four Knights in the Sicilian, so is with the sample line} 16. Re1 ({the d4-pawn is very vital, but Black can also make use of the very first opportunity to trade it, for instance} 16. Ng3 Bg6 17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Ne4 d3 $11) 16... Rc8 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Be4 Rfd8 19. Bxb7 Rb8 20. Be4 Na4 21. Rb1 Nc5 $5 ({an intriguing pawn sacrifice, though, generally speaking, there is nothing wrong with} 21... Nxb2 22. Qc1 Nc4 {, when all the pawns on the queenside are isolated and it will be extremely difficult for any of the players to make progress}) 22. Bd3 Ne6 $44 {[%cal Ge6f4]}) 8... c6 (8... Ng4 $5 9. Bf4 Bf6 10. Qd2 Nde5 11. Be2 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Re8 $11) 9. Rad1 ({In reply to} 9. a4 {Black can refine the idea from above by} Ng4 10. Bf4 Nge5 11. Be2 (11. Nxe5 $2 dxe5 12. Bxe5 {is just blundering a piece to} Bc5 $19) ({Black has a sensational idea up his sleeve against} 11. Bxe5 $6 dxe5 12. Nxe5 {, namely} Bc5 $1 13. Nxf7 Qe7 14. Nd6+ Kh8 15. Nxc8 Raxc8 {with tremendous activity -} 16. Qd2 Ne5 17. Be2 Rcd8 18. Qe1 Qh4 $40) 11... Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Ne5 13. Be2 (13. Bxe5 dxe5 14. Qxe5 {has won a pawn, but the dark-squared bishop, which does not have a counterpart, is a huge Black's asset, for instance} Bd6 15. Qh5 g6 16. Qh6 Qf6 $44) 13... Ng6 14. Bg3 (14. Be3 f5) 14... f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 $11) 9... b5 10. Be2 $8 Re8 $1 11. Bf4 {Concentrating on the vulnerable d6-pawn, but Black can react adequately against the one on e4.} (11. e5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qxe5 Bd7 14. Bf3 {seems to exert some pressure on the queenside, but Black can initiate counterplay by} Bf8 15. Qf4 b4 16. Ne2 Nd5 17. Rxd5 ({in case of} 17. Bxd5 cxd5 18. Rxd5 Qc8 {he will be also enjoying a long-term compensation due to the active bishops, e.g.} 19. Rd2 Bc6 $44) 17... cxd5 18. Bxd5 Be6 19. Bxa8 Qxa8 $40) (11. a4 a6 12. axb5 axb5 13. Bf4 {is neutralized by another clever tactical operation -} b4 $1 14. Qxb4 d5 15. Qd4 Bc5 16. Qd2 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Rxe4 18. Bd3 Rea4 $11) 11... Bb7 12. Bxd6 c5 13. Bxe7 (13. Qd2 b4 ({Black should be aware of} 13... Bxd6 $2 14. Bxb5 $1 $16) 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Nb5 {is, similarly to the main text, successfully met by the cool-blooded} Rad8 $1 {, defending Nd7 and preparing to win the e4-pawn back at the most appropriate moment, for example} 16. Qe3 (16. Nc7 Rf8) 16... Bxe4 17. Nc7 Bxf3 18. Qxe7 Rxe7 19. Bxf3 Kf8 $11) (13. Qd3 {is making} Bxd6 {possible, for instance} 14. Qxd6 b4 15. Nb5 Rxe4 16. Qd2 (16. Bd3 Re7) 16... Qe7 17. Rfe1 ({here is a prove why Black's potential should not be underestimated - the immediate} 17. Bd3 {is missing} Rg4 $1 18. Rfe1 Bxf3 $1 19. Rxe7 Rxg2+ 20. Kf1 Ng4 21. Ke1 Rg1+ 22. Bf1 Nxh2 {and, in order to stay in the game, White has to find the only moves} 23. Qd3 Nxf1 24. Rc1) 17... Re8 18. Bd3 Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Qd8 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. Nd6 Qb8 22. Nxb7 Qxb7 23. Bc4 h6 $11) 13... Qxe7 14. Qd6 (14. Qe3 a6 15. Nd2 b4 16. Ncb1 Nxe4 17. Nc4 Bc6 $11) 14... Qxd6 15. Rxd6 b4 16. Nd1 ({Black is going to regain the pawn with interest after} 16. Nb5 Rxe4 17. Rd2 Re7 18. Nd6 Bc6 {as well, White can already look for a repetition by} 19. Nf5) 16... Rad8 17. Bb5 Nb6 18. Rxf6 gxf6 19. Bxe8 Rxe8 $11 *

