 Qxe5 22. bxc6 Bf5 23. Qf3 Rae8 24. Ng5 (24. Nxc5 Qxc5 $11) 24... Qxe1+ 25. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 26. Kh2 Bd6+ 27. g3 g6 28. Qd5 (28. Bd5 Kg7 29. Kg2 Bxc2 $132) 28... Be7 29. g4 (29. Nxf7 $2 {runs into} Be4) 29... Be6 30. Nxe6 fxe6 31. Qd7 Rxf2+ 32. Kg3 {with beautiful perpetual after} Re3+ $1 33. Kxf2 Bh4+ 34. Kf1 Re1+ $11) 11... Ne5 12. h3 (12. Nd2 {[%cal Gf2f4]} Ng6 {is taking advantage of the fact Re1 does not support the thematic advance f2-f4.} 13. Ne2 c5 (13... d5 $5 14. exd5 Nxd5 {looks reasonable, but it makes sense to harass Bd4, especially when the weakness of the seemingly exposed d5-square is illusory}) 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Bd5 Bb7 16. Nc4 Bxd5 17. Qxd5 Rad8 18. c3 Ne7 19. Qh5 d5 20. exd5 Nxd5 $11) 12... Bd7 13. Nh4 {[%cal Gf2f4]} Rae8 {and Black, who has finished his mobilization, seems to be prepared to meet any action on the kingside:} 14. f4 (14. Qd2 Nh5 $5 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. exf5 Qc8 17. f4 (17. Bxe5 dxe5 18. Rxe5 Rd8 19. Qe2 Bd6 20. Re3 Qxf5 $11) 17... Nd7 18. g4 Nhf6 19. g5 Nh5 20. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4e2]} d5 21. Be2 g6 22. Bxh5 gxh5 23. Re2 Bb4 $132) 14... Ng6 15. Nxg6 hxg6 {may lead to a double-edged position after} 16. Qf3 Be6 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. e5 Nd5 19. Qg4 Kh7 $11) (8. a5 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ({a typical reaction to the march of the rook's pawn with b7-b5 to follow, Black can also insert} 8... Qc7) 9. Qe2 (9. Re1 b5 10. axb6 axb6 11. b4 (11. d5 $6 b5) (11. Bf1 Bb7 12. h3 Re8 $11) 11... b5 12. Bf1 h6 13. h3 Re8 $11) (9. Bd3 Re8 10. h3 b5 11. axb6 axb6 $11) (9. h3 b5 10. axb6 axb6 11. b4 exd4 (11... b5 12. Bb3 Qc7 {may transpose after 13.Be3 or 13.Qe2 to one of the next lines}) 12. Nxd4 Ne5 13. Bb3 c5 {(this counterstrike can also come in handy)} 14. Ndb5 cxb4 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Be6 17. Rb1 Qd7 18. Rxb4 Rfc8 $11) (9. Be3 b5 10. axb6 axb6 11. b4 b5 12. Bb3 Qc7 13. h3 (13. Qd2 Ng4 14. Bg5 Bxg5 15. Qxg5 Ngf6 16. Rfd1 Re8 $11) 13... c5 $1 14. bxc5 dxc5 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Bb7 $11) 9... b5 (9... exd4 10. Nxd4 Re8 {[%cal Ge8e2] is an alternative, but this consistent push is a direct shot at equality}) 10. axb6 axb6 11. d5 (11. Rd1 exd4 12. Nxd4 Ne5 13. Bf4 Qc7 $11) (11. b4 b5 12. Bb3 Qc7 13. h3 {is similar to a position from above with Qd1-e2 (aiming at the b5-pawn) instead of Bc1-e3. Here the liberating c6-c5 is hindered, but Black can also use a restrained strategy like} h6 14. Rd1 Re8 $132 {[%cal Ge7f8]}) 11... b5 $1 12. dxc6 bxc4 13. cxd7 Bxd7 14. Nd2 (14. Qxc4 Be6 15. Qe2 h6 16. Rd1 Qc7 $44) 14... Be6 15. Nxc4 Rb4 $1 16. Nd2 (16. b3 Qc7 $11) 16... d5 17. exd5 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 $11) (8. Ba2 {is a prophylactic measure against the exchange operation with Nxe4, but Black can find a way to the central pawn by the relatively rare, but fully playable} exd4 $5 ({known are} 8... a5) (8... Re8) ({and} 8... h6) 9. Nxd4 ({we are still going to see of} 9. Qxd4 Nc5 {, keeping an eye on the e4-pawn and Bc8-e6 coming next.} 10. h3 (10. Rd1 Bg4 $132) 10... a5 11. Be3 Be6 12. Bxe6 Nxe6 13. Qc4 Re8 $11 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gf6d7]}) 9... Nc5 10. Re1 (10. Qf3 a5 (10... Re8) 11. h3 Be6 12. Rd1 Qc7 13. Bf4 Rad8 $11) (10. f3 {allows} d5 $1 11. exd5 (11. e5 Ne8 12. f4 f6 $132) 11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. c3 a5 {[%csl Ra4] , fixing the queenside pawns in return for the isolated one on d5.} 14. Re1 Re8 $11) 10... Re8 {[%cal Ge7f8]} 11. Qf3 (11. f3 Bf8 12. Kh1 h6 $11) (11. h3 $144 Bf8 12. Qf3) 11... Bf8 12. h3 {- 8.h3}) 8... exd4 $5 ({Other options are} 8... Re8) (8... h6) ({, as well as} 8... Nxe4 9. Nxe4 d5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 dxc4 12. Nd6 f6 13. Bf4 Be6 14. Ra3 fxe5 15. Bxe5 Bxd6 16. Bxd6 Rf6 {, which is close to equality.}) 9. Nxd4 {A natural move, otherwise White might have trouble with his e4-pawn.} (9. Qxd4 Nc5 10. Rd1 (10. Re1 {does not stop} Ncxe4 $1 11. Nxe4 d5 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 $11) 10... Be6 11. Bf4 (11. a5 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 b5 13. axb6 axb6 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 $11) (11. Be3 a5 12. Bxe6 Nxe6 13. Qc4 Re8 $11 {[%cal Ge7f8]}) 11... a5 $1 12. Bh2 ({analogous to the text is} 12. Bg3 h6 $5 13. Bxe6 Nxe6 14. Qe3 Re8 15. e5 Nd7 16. exd6 Bf6 17. Rab1 $140 Nec5 18. Qd2 Qb6 19. Nd4 Qb4 $44) 12... h6 $5 13. Bxe6 Nxe6 14. Qe3 Re8 $1 15. e5 Nd7 16. exd6 Bf6 17. Ne4 ({an intersting try with a tempting queen sacrifice in mind; Black seems in good shape after both} 17. Nd2 Nec5 18. Nce4 Bxb2 19. Rab1 Be5 20. Bxe5 Rxe5 21. f4 Rd5 $11) ({and} 17. Rab1 Nec5 18. Qd2 Qb6 $44) 17... Bxb2 18. Rab1 Nec5 19. Qxc5 $5 Nxc5 20. Nxc5 Ba3 21. Nxb7 Qd7 22. Ne5 {and now:} Qf5 ({with} 22... Rxe5 23. Bxe5 {Black is investing less material in the fight with the advanced passed pawn, the position seems dynamically balanced -} Ra7 ({similar is} 23... f6 24. Bf4 Ra7 25. Rb3 $140 Rxb7 26. Rxa3 Qf5 27. Rc3 Qxf4 28. d7 Rxd7 29. Rxd7 Qc1+ 30. Kh2 Qf4+ $11) ({the active queen must provide Black with sufficient counterplay after} 23... Rb8 24. Rb3 Rxb7 25. Rxa3 Qf5 26. Rad3 Qxe5 27. d7 Rxd7 28. Rxd7 Qe2 29. c3 g5 30. g4 Qc2 $132 {/=}) ({solid enough is} 23... Bb4 24. c3 Qxb7 25. cxb4 axb4 26. a5 Qd7 27. Rxb4 Rxa5 28. Bg3 Rd5 $11) 24. Rb3 Bb4 (24... Rxb7 {- 23....Rb8}) 25. c3 Rxb7 26. cxb4 axb4 27. a5 Ra7 28. Rxb4 Rxa5 29. Bg3 Rd5 {and after} 30. Re1 {Black can already get rid of the annoying pawn or just keep the control over the d7-square, for instance} c5 31. Rbe4 Kh7 32. Kh2 Qf5 (32... Qc6 33. Re7 Rxd6 34. Bxd6 Qxd6+ 35. Kg1 Qd2 $132 {/=}) 33. Re5 Qd3 $11) {is a more complicated way to claim counterplay -} 23. d7 Rxe5 24. Bxe5 Qxe5 25. Re1 Qf5 26. Re8+ Kh7 27. Rxa8 Qxd7 28. Nxa5 Qd4 {[%cal Gd4a4]} 29. Nb7 Qd2 30. Rf1 Qb4 $132) 9... Re8 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gd7c5]} (9... d5 {is also possible, but Black will have to work for the desired equality after} 10. exd5 Nb6 11. Bb3 Nbxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qf3 $1 Bc5 14. Ne2 Be6 15. Ng3 $14) 10. Ba2 (10. Nf5 {can claim a pair of bishops, but this idea is time-consuming and Black can extend his lead in development after} Nc5 $1 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. f3 Be6 $11) (10. Bg5 Nc5 (10... Nf8 11. Re1 Ng6) (10... Ne5 11. Bb3) 11. Qf3 (11. Re1 h6) 11... Be6 $1 12. Nxe6 Nxe6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. e5 Nd5 15. Bxe7 Rxe7 {and, though White can leave the opponent with an isolated e6-pawn and exert some pressure on it, the position seems closer to equality, for example} 16. exd6 ({White has compensation, but hardly more after} 16. Ne4 dxe5 17. Rad1 Qc7 18. Rfe1 {, for example} Rf8 19. Qa3 b6 20. c4 Nf6 21. Nxf6+ Rxf6 22. Rd6 Rd7 23. Red1 Rxd6 24. Qxd6 Qxd6 25. Rxd6 c5 26. b3 e4 27. Kf1 e3 28. f3 e5 29. Rd8+ Rf8 30. Rd7 e4 31. Ke2 exf3+ 32. gxf3 Rf7 {with a probable repetition}) 16... Qxd6 17. Ne4 Qe5 18. b3 Rf8 19. Qe2 Nf4 20. Qe3 Qh5 21. Rae1 Qg6 22. Qg3 Qf5 23. Qg4 Rd7 {etc.}) (10. Re1 {is less pretending, the rooks on the e-file enable} d5 $1 11. exd5 Nb6 12. Bb3 Nbxd5 $11) 10... Nc5 11. Re1 Bf8 12. Qf3 Ne6 $1 13. Bxe6 {White's best bet.} (13. Nf5 Nc5 $1 14. Bg5 Bxf5 15. Qxf5 Re5 16. Qf4 h6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Qxf6 gxf6 $11) (13. Nxe6 Bxe6 14. Bg5 Bxa2 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Qxf6 gxf6 17. Nxa2 Re5 $11 {[%cal Gf6f5]}) 13... fxe6 (13... Bxe6 $6 14. Bg5) 14. e5 dxe5 15. Nde2 {Directing the knight towards the important e4-square.} (15. Nb3 {misplaces it, so it is time for} e4 $1 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 e5 18. Be3 Qf6 $11) 15... e4 $1 16. Nxe4 ({No improvement is} 16. Qg3 e5 17. Bg5 Bf5 18. Rad1 Qe7 19. Qe3 Bg6 $11) 16... Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Qd5 (17... e5 $144) 18. Ng3 (18. Qh4 e5 19. Ng3 a5 20. Be3 Qf7 $11) (18. Nc3 Qxe4 19. Nxe4 {-19. Nxe4.}) 18... Qxe4 19. Rxe4 (19. Nxe4 e5 20. f3 (20. a5 h6 {[%cal Gc8f5]}) 20... Bf5 21. Bg5 a5 22. Re2 b5 $11) 19... c5 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7c6]} (19... e5 {is another way to activate the second bishop, even at the cost of this pawn -} 20. Bd2 Be6 $1 21. Rxe5 Bf7 22. Rxe8 Rxe8 23. Be3 a5 $44) 20. Bf4 Bd7 {In the view of the vulnerable isolated e6-pawn White retains certain pressure, but the pair of bishops and the open d-file, as well as a potential ending with opposite-coloured bishops, must be enough to hold and compensate that weakness, for example} 21. Be5 Red8 22. Nh5 Be8 23. Nf4 Rd2 24. c4 Bc6 25. Re3 Re8 26. Bc3 Rd6 27. b3 g6 {[%cal Gf8h6]} 28. Be5 Rd2 29. Rae1 Bh6