ons are} 10... Ng4 11. Bd2 Bf8) ({and} 10... a5 $5) 11. Nxd4 Bf8 12. f3 (12. Qf3 Nc5 $132) 12... Ne5 13. Kh1 ({in reply to} 13. Qd2 {Black is ready to strike with} d5 $1 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 {I will refer the readers to Chapter 5 and the remark about the same pawn structure and the a4-pawn in particular, here the c4-forepost is yet another bonus for Black -} 16. Bf2 Nc4 $132 17. Qd3 (17. Rxe8 Qxe8 18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. Qc3 Be6 20. Re1 Qxa4 21. Nxe6 fxe6 22. Rxe6 Rc8 $11) 17... Bd7 $1 {with ample compensation for the sacrificed pawn -} 18. Rxe8 Bxe8 19. Bxc4 dxc4 20. Qxc4 Rc8 21. Qb3 Rc7 22. Re1 a6 23. c3 Qc8 $44 {[%csl Ge8,Gf8]}) (13. Bf2 Bd7 14. Qd2 Ng6 15. Kh1 b6 $5 {[%cal Ga7a6] can be considered a critical position, by his last move Black is trying to build a hedgehog structure on the queenside:} 16. f4 (16. Rad1 a6 {[%cal Gb6b5] and White must reckon with all these mobile pawns}) (16. Be3 a6 17. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5]} b5 (17... d5 $5) 18. g5 hxg5 19. Bxg5 bxa4 20. Rg1 Rb8 $132) 16... a6 17. Nf3 b5 18. e5 (18. f5 Ne5 19. Bh4 Rc8 {(d5)} 20. axb5 axb5 $132) 18... b4 $1 19. exf6 (19. Nd1 Nh5 $1 20. exd6 $140 Qf6 $132) 19... bxc3 20. Qxc3 Rxe1+ 21. Nxe1 Nxf4 ({or} 21... Qxf6 22. Qxf6 gxf6 23. g3 d5 $11) 22. fxg7 Bxg7 23. Qd2 Qf6 $132) 13... Ng6 14. Qd2 {is on the verge of transposing to the last subline,} ({so is with} 14. Bg1 Bd7) {, but there is once again the forcing} 14... d5 $5 15. exd5 cxd5 {and now:} 16. Nde2 (16. a5 b6 17. axb6 axb6 18. Bg1 Bc5 19. Rxe8+ Qxe8 20. Re1 Qd7 $11) (16. Bf2 Rxe1+ 17. Rxe1 (17. Qxe1 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gf8c5]}) 17... Bb4 {[%csl Gb4]} 18. Rd1 Bd7 $11) 16... Bb4 {[%csl Gb4]} 17. Bd4 (17. Ng3 b6 18. Rad1 Bb7 19. Bd4 Rc8 20. Rxe8+ Nxe8 21. Nf5 Qd7 22. Ne3 Ne7 23. Bb3 Qe6 $11) 17... Bd7 {is reminding of the a4-pawn:} 18. Bb3 {is overprotecting the pawns on the queenside, when:} (18. Nf4 Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Bxa4 20. Nxg6 fxg6 21. Qd3 {is a serious try to get away from the multiple pins, to which Black seems to hold by exchanges -} Bxc3 22. Qxc3 Rc8 {, for example} 23. Bxf6 (23. Qb4 Bxc2 24. Qxb7 Rc7 $11) 23... gxf6 24. Qe3 Kg7 (24... Be8 $5 25. Qxh6 $140 Qa5 26. Rxe8+ Rxe8 27. Qxg6+ $11) 25. Qxa7 Bxc2 26. Qxb7+ Rc7 27. Qxd5 Qxd5 28. Bxd5 Rc5 {Rb5 and Black's active rook is nullifying the value of the opponent's extra pawn}) 18... a5 {is a calm and sensible multifunctional move - by bringing his own a-pawn in safety Black is fixing the target as well:} (18... Nh5 $5 {is a curious pawn sacrifice:} 19. Bxd5 {looks principled, after} (19. g4 {is declining it, after} Nf6 20. Ng3 {Black can regroup by means of} Nf8 $1 21. Qd3 $140 Bc6 22. Rxe8 Nxe8 23. Rd1 Ne6 24. Be5 (24. Nf5 Nf6 $11) 24... Nc5 {and the elimination of Bb3 will release the pressure on the isolated d5-pawn, for instance} 25. Qd4 Bxc3 26. Qxc3 (26. bxc3 Ne6) 26... Nxb3 27. cxb3 Rc8 $11) 19... Qh4 {White can harass this annoying guest by} 20. Be3 (20. g4 Bd6 21. Bg1 Nf6 22. Bxb7 Rab8 23. Qxd6 Rxb7 $132) 20... Rad8 21. Qd4 Qe7 {, though his own queen will have to look for a safe place, for example} 22. Qc4 Bc6 23. Bxc6 Ne5 24. Qb3 Nxc6 25. Bf2 Na5 26. Qa2 Qc7 27. Rad1 a6 $44) 19. Ng3 (19. Rad1 b5 $1 20. axb5 Bxb5 $11) (19. Nf4 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Nxf4 21. Qxf4 Nh5 $1 22. Qd2 (22. Qe5 Qh4 23. Bxd5 Bd6 $1 24. Bxf7+ Kh8 25. Qxd6 Qxe1+ 26. Bg1 Nf6 $132) 22... Bc6 23. g3 Nf6 24. Qd3 Qd6 25. Kg2 Nd7 $11) 19... Bc6 20. Rxe8+ (20. Rad1 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Nf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8e6]}) (20. Nf5 Re6 21. Rad1 Qd7 $11) 20... Nxe8 21. Nf5 (21. Rd1 Nc7 $11) 21... Qd7 22. Ne3 Nc7 $11) (9. a5 Re8 {is quite similar to the leading text:} 10. Bf1 (10. d5 b5 $1 11. Ba2 (11. Bf1 cxd5 12. Nxd5 Rb8 $11) 11... b4 12. dxc6 bxc3 13. cxd7 Bxd7 14. bxc3 Qc7 $44) (10. h3 {is just transposing}) 10... exd4 11. Nxd4 Bf8 12. h3 (12. Bf4 Nc5 13. f3 d5 14. e5 ({White will probably have to reconcile himself with} 14. exd5 Rxe1 15. Qxe1 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 17. Rd1 Bf5 18. c3 Ne6 $11) 14... Nh5 15. Bd2 {(here is exactly a moment, in which White is badly missing h2-h3)} {and here with the harsh} g5 $132 {[%cal Gh5g7] Black will strengthen the siege of the e5-pawn}) 12... Nc5 13. f3 (13. Qf3 Qe7 $132) 13... Bd7 14. Bf4 b6 $5 15. a6 d5 16. e5 Nh7 $132) (9. Bf1 Re8 10. h3 {see 10.Bf1 below;} (10. a5 {- 9.a5 Re8 10.Bf1})) 9... Re8 10. a5 ({Here} 10. Be3 {, as well as on the next move(s), is creating the strategical threat d4-d5, so it is time for} exd4 $1 (10... Bf8 $143 $6 11. d5 $1 Nb6 12. Bb3 $14) 11. Qxd4 (11. Bxd4 {controls the e5-square and the e4-pawn is defended, so it makes sense for Black to refrain from an automatic retreat Be7-f8 and use this vacated square for} Nf8 $1 {[%cal Gc8e6]} 12. Qd2 (12. a5 Be6 {Consequent and good - the battle for the d5-square is on!} 13. Bf1 Ng6 14. Qd2 ({in reply to} 14. b4 {, amongst all, Black has} b5 $1 15. axb6 axb6 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. Bxb6 Qa3 18. Qa1 Qxa1 19. Rxa1 {and now} d5 $1 20. exd5 $140 Bxd5 21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22. Bc5 Nxb4 $11) 14... c5 $5 15. Bxf6 (15. Be3 a6 $11) 15... Bxf6 $11) 12... Be6 (12... Ne6 $5 13. Be3 Nxe4 $1 14. Nxe4 d5 15. Bxh6 dxc4 $1 $11) 13. Bd3 (13. Bxe6 Nxe6 $11 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ge7f8]}) (13. Bf1 Ng6 $11) 13... Ng6 14. a5 (14. Nh2 Nh5 {[%cal Ge7g5]}) 14... Qc7 $11) ({in case of} 11. Nxd4 Bf8 {, pressing on the e4-pawn, is already fully justified, as confirmed by} 12. Bf4 (12. Bd2 a5 $132) 12... Nc5 13. Qf3 Ncxe4 14. Nxe4 Rxe4 15. Bxf7+ Kxf7 16. Rxe4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Qf6 $11) 11... Nf8 {[%cal Gc8e6]} ({Here is this subtle manoeuvre again; possible are the continuations} 11... Qa5) ({and} 11... Bf8 {, though the latter does not attack the e4-pawn}) 12. Rad1 (12. a5 Be6) 12... Be6 13. Bf4 a6 $1 14. b3 (14. Bf1 d5 $11) 14... Bxc4 (14... Qa5 $5) 15. Qxc4 Ng6 16. Bg3 Bf8 17. Qb4 (17. e5 d5 18. Qd4 Nd7 $132) 17... Ne5 $1 18. Qxb7 (18. Nxe5 $6 dxe5 {[%csl Rb4]} 19. Qxb7 $140 $4 Qa5 $19) 18... Qa5 $1 19. b4 {Here this intermezzo is saving the day for White, his crippled kingside structure after} Nxf3+ 20. gxf3 Qh5 {is a precondition for a perpetual in the long run, for example} 21. Kg2 Reb8 22. Qc7 d5 23. Qxc6 (23. Ne2 dxe4 24. fxe4 Rc8 25. Qf4 Bxb4 26. c3 Ba5 27. e5 Nd5 28. Qc4 Qf5 $11) 23... Rc8 24. Qb7 Rxc3 25. Qxa8 Qxf3+ 26. Kg1 (26. Kh2 $6 Rxc2 {[%cal Gc2f2]}) 26... Nh5 $1 27. Bd6 (27. Qb8 Rxc2 28. exd5 Rxf2 29. Bxf2 Nf4 30. Qxf4 Qxf4 31. Re8 Qxb4 32. d6 Qxa4 33. Rde1 Qb5 $11) 27... Rxc2 28. Qxf8+ Kh7 29. Rf1 Qxh3 30. Qxf7 Qg4+ 31. Kh1 Qh3+ 32. Bh2 Ng3+ 33. Kg1 Ne2+ $11) ({in case of the direct} 10. d5 {White should consider} Nb6 11. Bb3 a5 {, when the central structure will be determined by the opponent, for example} 12. Qd3 Bd7 13. Be3 cxd5 14. exd5 Rc8 {and the latter can oppose further actions on the queenside after} 15. Nd2 (15. Qe2 Nh7 $132) {with the original manoeuvre} 15... Nh5 $1 16. Nb5 Nf4 {, eliminating a key piece like the dark-squared bishop. Black's chances are not worse -} 17. Bxf4 exf4 18. c3 Bf8 $11) (10. Bf1 {is a sort of prophylaxis, including for playing d4-d5. Black, with regard to the latter, can continue with} b6 (10... a5 $5 {is, as usual, an option}) 11. d5 (11. a5 bxa5 (11... b5 12. d5 b4 13. dxc6 bxc3 14. cxd7 Bxd7 15. bxc3 Qc7 $40) 12. Be3 Bf8 13. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4]} d5 $1 14. dxe5 Nxe5 $11) (11. Be3 a6 12. dxe5 (12. d5 cxd5 13. Nxd5 Bb7 14. Nxe7+ Rxe7 $5 15. Qxd6 Re6 16. Qa3 Bxe4 $11) 12... dxe5 (12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Qxd8 Bxd8 15. Red1 Bc7 16. b4 Rd8 {is also solid}) 13. Nh4 Nc5 14. Qxd8 (14. Qf3 Qc7 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Bxe6 Nxe6 17. Nf5 Rad8 $11) 14... Rxd8 15. Nf3 (15. Bc4 Kf8 16. Nf3 Ncd7) 15... Nfd7 16. Rad1 Bb7 $11) 11... cxd5 $1 (11... Bb7 $143 12. dxc6 Bxc6 13. Bb5 $1 Bb7 14. Nh4 a6 15. Bf1 $14 Nc5 $140 16. Nf5 $1) 12. exd5 ({the piece control over the key d5-square after} 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 (13. exd5 Nf6 $132) 13... Rb8 {is far from a stable one, Black will attack it pretty soon -} 14. Bc4 Rf8 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7]}) 12... Bb7 13. Ra3 a6 14. Nh4 $5 Nxd5 15. Nf5 {, with an idea for a rook lift to g3, which can be prevented by} N5f6 {, returning the pawn, but Black's more harmonious development and control over the central squares after} 16. Nxd6 Bxd6 17. Qxd6 Re6 18. Qd3 Qe7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5] seem to counterbalance the potential power of the enmy bishops}) (10. Ba2 exd4 $1 ({White will have an extra opportunity to this after} 10... Bf8 11. Be3) (10... a5 $5) 11. Nxd4 ({as we already knw,} 11. Qxd4 {is best met by} Nf8 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 11... Bf8 {and now:} 12. f4 (12. Bf4 Nc5 13. e5 (13. Qf3 Ne6 14. Nxe6 Bxe6 $11) 13... dxe5 14. Bxe5 a5 $11) (12. Qf3 d5 $132) (12. a5 {is not helpful for the security of the e4-pawn, Black has every reason to attack it by} Nc5 $1 13. Qf3 {and fight for the advantage by} d5 $5 (13... Ne6) 14. e5 Nfe4 15. Rxe4 (15. Nxe4 Rxe5 $1) 15... Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Rxe5 $1 17. Ng3 Re1+ 18. Kh2 Qxa5 19. Qf4 g5 $1 20. Qf3 Rxc1 21. Nb3 Rxa1 22. Nxa5 Rxa2 23. Nb3 Ra4) 12... a6 $1 ({here} 12... Nc5 {looks a bit premature because of} 13. e5 dxe5 14. fxe5 Nh7 15. Kh1 $14) 13. Kh1 (13. Kh2 Qc7 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) (13. a5 Qc7 14. Qf3 b5 15. axb6 Nxb6 16. Nde2 Bb7 17. Ng3 c5 18. Bd2 a5 19. Kh2 a4 $11) 13... Qc7 14. Qd3 (14. Nf5 d5 $132) (14. Qf3 b5 15. axb5 c5 $1 $132) (14. Bd2 b5 15. axb5 cxb5 $132) 14... b5 15. axb5 cxb5 $132 16. Qg3 $140 Nc5 17. e5 dxe5 18. fxe5 Kh8 19. Bf4 Nh5 20. Qf3 Nxf4 21. Qxa8 Nxh3 22. Qf3 Ng5 23. Qf4 Bb7 $44) 10... Bf8 {A useful prophylactic and waiting move compared to:} (10... Qc7 11. Bf1 Nf8 12. d5 Bd7 13. Nd2 $14) (10... Rb8 11. Bf1 b5 12. axb6 axb6 13. d5 $14) (10... exd4 11. Nxd4 Bf8 {allows White to play} 12. Bf4 {in one go with certain initiative -} Nc5 13. Qf3 Ne6 14. Be3 Ng5 15. Bxg5 hxg5 16. a6 $14) 11. Be3 (11. dxe5 $5 {is usually not pretending for much, but Black has to show precision:} dxe5 {is natural, the only question is whether White will be able to organize anything aubstantial on the kingside:} (11... Nxe5 $6 {is not accurate because of the simple} 12. Nxe5 dxe5 (12... Rxe5 13. Bf4 Re8 14. Bd3 Be6 15. Ne2 $14) 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 {with a lasting edge after} 14. Be3 $14) 12. Nh4 {can really pose problems on the light squares, Black is therefore well-advised to make use of the extra opportunity} ({to} 12. g4 $5 {[%cal Gg4g5]} {Black should react with} Nh7 $1 13. Kh2 $140 Qc7 14. g5 (14. Rg1 $144 Nc5 15. g5 hxg5 16. Nxg5) 14... hxg5 15. Rg1 (15. Nxg5 $144 Nxg5 16. Bxg5 Nc5) 15... Nc5 16. Nxg5 Nxg5 17. Bxg5 Be6 18. Be2 Qd6 19. Qf1 Bc8 $1 20. Rd1 Qg6 21. Be3 Qf6 22. Bg5 $11) 12... Bc5 $1 ({there is no clear road to equality in case of} 12... Nc5 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Ng6 $1 Bd6 15. f4 $1 Be6 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. fxe5 Nfd7 18. Bf1 Nxe5 19. Be3 $14) 13. Qf3 (13. Nf5 {is yet another principled follow-up of the trade in the center, Black can initiate counterplay by means of} b5 $1 14. axb6 Nxb6 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Bd3 {with decent play on the queenside after} Be6 {at once or after 16...a5}) ({harmless is} 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Rxe3 Nf8 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Nf3 Ng6 $11) 13... Nf8 {Not only covering the g6-square, but also directing this knight towards the attractive one on d4, which has been exposed exactly by White's pawn exchange.} 14. Ra4 (14. Qg3 Nh5 15. Qf3 Nf6 $11) (14. Rd1 Qe7) 14... Ne6 15. Bxe6 (15. Nf5 Nd4 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Nb1 Be6 $11) 15... Bxe6 16. Nf5 Kh7 (16... Bd4 $5) 17. Rd1 Nd7 18. g4 Rg8 $1 19. Ne2 Bf8 {[%cal Gg7g6]} 20. Qe3 (20. Neg3 g6) 20... Qc7 21. Ra1 Rd8 $11 {A. Chronopoulos - J. Bourgault, ICCF email, 2023.}) (11. d5 {is logically connected to White's previous move, but here it can be strongly countered with} b5 $1 (11... cxd5 {is playing straight into White's hands -} 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 $14) 12. axb6 ({after} 12. Bb3 cxd5 {is already justified due to the possibility to meet} 13. Nxd5 {with} Bb7 14. c4 bxc4 15. Bxc4 Rc8 16. b3 a6 $11) 12... Nxb6 13. Bb3 cxd5 14. exd5 a5 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd8c7] and it is Black, who will use his a-pawn for active play on the queenside.}) ({Both} 11. Bf1 exd4 12. Nxd4 Nc5 {and}) (11. Ba2 exd4 12. Nxd4 (12. Qxd4 Nc5) 12... Nc5 {are likely to transpose to lines from above.}) 11... exd4 $1 {A well-timed exchange.} ({With the bishop already placed on e3 the strategical threat d4-d5 is real, as shown by} 11... Qc7 $6 12. d5 $1 cxd5 13. Bxd5 $16) 12. Bxd4 (12. Qxd4 {is also met by} b5 $1 {e.g.} 13. axb6 Nxb6 14. Bf1 (14. Bb3 Qc7 15. Qd3 Nfd7 $11) 14... c5 15. Qd2 a5 16. b3 Bb7 17. e5 dxe5 18. Qxd8 Rexd8 19. Nxe5 Bd6 20. Nd3 Rdc8 $11) 12... b5 $1 (12... Qc7 {is untimely again -} 13. b4 $5 (13. Nh4 $5 Ne5 14. Be2) 13... Ne5 14. Bf1 $14) 13. axb6 Nxb6 14. Bb3 {The best square for retreating the bishop.} (14. Bd3 a5 15. b3 Bb7 $132) (14. Bf1 a5 15. e5 (15. Nd2 a4 16. f4 Nfd7 $11) 15... dxe5 16. Rxe5 c5 17. Rxe8 Nxe8 $11) (14. Ba2 Be6 {is almost the same as in the main text - Black should neutralize the annoying bishop before it gains in power after a central break.}) 14... Be6 15. Bxe6 (15. Nd2 Bxb3 16. Nxb3 c5 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11) 15... Rxe6 16. Ra6 {Blocking the a7-pawn, the other options are failing to impress:} (16. e5 dxe5 17. Bxe5 Qe7 $11) (16. b3 a5 17. Qd3 Nbd7 18. Bxf6 Rxf6 19. Nd4 Nc5 $11) (16. Qd3 a5 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. Nd4 Qc7 19. b3 Qb7 $11) 16... Ne8 {[%cal Ge8c7]} 17. Be3 (17. Qa1 c5 18. Be3 Nf6 $1 {, as in Vignesh - Sriram, Pune, 2023, is very close to full equality, for example} 19. Bf4 Qe8 $1 {, based on} 20. Rxa7 Rxa7 21. Qxa7 Nbd5 $1 22. Nxd5 Nxd5 23. Bd2 Rxe4 24. Rxe4 Qxe4 25. Qa8 Nf6 26. Qxe4 Nxe4 $11) (17. Qd3 c5 18. Be3 {will just transpose.}) 17... c5 18. Qd3 Nc7 19. Ra5 {The last real attempt to press.} (19. Raa1 {enables Black's plan for} d5 20. exd5 $140 Ncxd5 21. Nxd5 Qxd5 22. Qxd5 Nxd5 23. Bd2 Rb6 24. b3 Nb4 $11) 19... d5 $1 {Nevertheless!} 20. exd5 Ncxd5 21. Bxc5 (21. Nxd5 Nxd5 $11 {[%csl Ra5]}) 21... Bxc5 (21... Rxe1+ 22. Nxe1 Bxc5 {leads to the same.}) 22. Nxd5 {This is the way to claim minimal material advantage at least.} (22. Rxe6 Bxf2+ 23. Kxf2 fxe6 24. Nxd5 Nxd5 $11) 22... Rxe1+ 23. Nxe1 Rc8 24. Ne3 {Again the only practical chance.} (24. Nc3 {is running into the familiar motif} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Ra5] (see the note to move 21)} 25. Ra1 Nxc3 26. Qxd8+ Rxd8 27. bxc3 Rd2 28. Nd3 Bd6 $1 29. Rc1 Ba3 30. Ra1 Bd6 $11) 24... Qxd3 25. cxd3 Bb4 26. Ra1 Bxe1 27. Rxe1 Na4 $1 $44 28. b4 {Trying to keep the vulnerable isolated pawns on the board as long as possible.} (28. Nf5 Rb8 $11) (28. Rb1 Rd8 $11) 28... Nb2 29. d4 Rb8 30. Nf5 (30. d5 Nd3 31. Ra1 Rxb4 32. Rxa7 Rb1+ 33. Kh2 Nxf2 $13) (30. Nd5 {would have been White's best, for example} Nd3 31. Rb1 Kf8 ({another opportunity is} 31... Rb5 32. Ne7+ Kf8 33. Nc6 a6 {, followed by a timely Rb5-b6}) 32. Kf1 Rd8 33. Ke2 Ne5 $1 {The tactical point of Black's play - in the ensuing rook ending he will limit the number of the pawns to the minimum by means of} 34. dxe5 Rxd5 35. f4 g5 $1 36. g3 gxf4 37. gxf4 f6 $11) 30... Nd3 (30... Rxb4 $11) 31. Re7 a6 32. d5 Nxb4 33. d6 Rd8 34. Kh2 Nd5 35. Ra7 Nf6 36. Rxa6 Ne8 37. d7 (37. g4 Kh7 {[%cal Gg7g6] (g6) will gradually eliminate the passed pawn. The textmove is leading by force to a rook ending, in which White's etra pawn is only of symbolic value.}) 37... Rxd7 38. Ra8 Kf8 39. Nxg7 Kxg7 40. Rxe8 $11 {R. Vlasak - A .Babasyan, ICCF email, 2021} *

